ULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-08-02 06:40:56','2018-02-01 03:49:37','2018-02-01 14:19:37'),(81,172,4,0,104,'Darrin Burgmann',NULL,NULL,'darrinburgmann',0,'Nowra, NSW 2016','Chances are I could be found in just about any state - unconscious due to low blood pressure or suffering an attack of some variety - so at least if a member of the public or a paramedic can look at my wrist and see what is wrong, then they&rsquo;ll know what to do, or at least who to call &ndash; my Mum,&rdquo; said Darrin.','<p>Walking into his home in Nowra New South Wales, you would have no idea that MedicAlert member Darrin Burgmann even has a medical condition, and yet, this former nurse of nine years has one of the rarest and most debilitating conditions on the planet.<br /><br />Six years ago, while he was still working as a nurse, the now 41-year-old began noticing he was forgetting things and said certain tasks seemed to be becoming more difficult.<br /><br />&ldquo;I really had no idea what was going on, and despite a growing range of bizarre symptoms and an even bigger list of tests I was undertaking, no one had any answers, other than to say &lsquo;you&rsquo;re losing your mind&rsquo; or &lsquo;you must be making this up&rsquo;,&rdquo; said Darrin.<br /><br />&ldquo;While I knew that wasn&rsquo;t true, many of my behaviours - suddenly dropping things, seeing objects, almost blacking out or having my limbs fling out randomly - seemed to suggest something wasn&rsquo;t right.&rdquo;<br /><br />After four years of tests and devastating speculation about his mental state, Darrin was diagnosed with Multiple System Atrophy (MSA) or Shy-Drager Syndrome (SDS) which is a rare degenerative condition resulting from deterioration of certain nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord.<br /><br />&ldquo;When I was finally diagnosed in June 2015, I was both relieved and devastated. Relieved to know that I wasn&rsquo;t mad and that all these trips to hospital were in fact justified, but also devastated, because I had a chronic incurable disease with a short life-span,&rdquo; said Darrin.<br /><br />&ldquo;I&rsquo;d already had my stomach and kidneys shutdown and had endured issues with my heart, bladder and pancreas &ndash; most of which saw me rushed to hospital in the back of an ambulance.&rdquo;<br /><br />But, while he was (and still is) facing a completely unpredictable set of symptoms that could present at any time, Darrin said he wanted to try and continue living as normal a life as possible.<br /><br />&ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t want my life to be over, so I began looking into measures that would allow me to retain some quality of life and most importantly the independence we all enjoy,&rdquo; said Darrin.<br /><br />&ldquo;I&rsquo;d often heard patients talking about the freedom and security they felt from using a MedicAlert bracelet, because it had information about their condition, allergies and gave their emergency contact details, which for me is so important, because my Mum and sister are really the two who know most about my illness.&rdquo;<br /><br />Darrin said that with diabetes, an allergy to certain medications and peanuts, as well as a host of issues relating to his MSA, he&rsquo;d be silly not to have this documented, so that emergency responders can treat him correctly.<br /><br />&ldquo;Chances are I could be found in just about any state - unconscious due to low blood pressure or suffering an attack of some variety - so at least if a member of the public or a paramedic can look at my wrist and see what is wrong, then they&rsquo;ll know what to do, or at least who to call &ndash; my Mum,&rdquo; said Darrin.<br /><br />First discovered in 1960, MSA impacts around one in 10,000 people (or around 2300 Australians) and is most known for attacking the autonomic or involuntary nervous system (which controls blood pressure, heart rate, and bladder function) and the motor system (which controls balance and muscle movement). This often means people with MSA will often present with a variety of disorders and complications, many of which can be similar to Parkinson&rsquo;s disease.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Darrin Burgmann',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-08-22 13:09:26','2016-10-01 03:30:44','2016-10-01 13:00:32'),(82,172,4,0,104,'Darrin Burgmann',NULL,NULL,'darrinburgmann',0,'Nowra, NSW, member since','Chances are I could be found in just about any state - unconscious due to low blood pressure or suffering an attack of some variety - so at least if a member of the public or a paramedic can look at my wrist and see what is wrong, then they&rsquo;ll know what to do, or at least who to call &ndash; my Mum,&rdquo; said Darrin.','<p>Walking into his home in Nowra New South Wales, you would have no idea that MedicAlert member Darrin Burgmann even has a medical condition, and yet, this former nurse of nine years has one of the rarest and most debilitating conditions on the planet.<br /><br />Six years ago, while he was still working as a nurse, the now 41-year-old began noticing he was forgetting things and said certain tasks seemed to be becoming more difficult.<br /><br />&ldquo;I really had no idea what was going on, and despite a growing range of bizarre symptoms and an even bigger list of tests I was undertaking, no one had any answers, other than to say &lsquo;you&rsquo;re losing your mind&rsquo; or &lsquo;you must be making this up&rsquo;,&rdquo; said Darrin.<br /><br />&ldquo;While I knew that wasn&rsquo;t true, many of my behaviours - suddenly dropping things, seeing objects, almost blacking out or having my limbs fling out randomly - seemed to suggest something wasn&rsquo;t right.&rdquo;<br /><br />After four years of tests and devastating speculation about his mental state, Darrin was diagnosed with Multiple System Atrophy (MSA) or Shy-Drager Syndrome (SDS) which is a rare degenerative condition resulting from deterioration of certain nerve cells in the brain and s