hed in the middle of a busy street,&rdquo; Skye says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;After being knocked to the ground, repeatedly punched in the head and kicked to the back of my skull and ribs I was barely conscious when an ambulance arrived.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The paramedics put me in a spinal collar and strapped me to a board, and even though I could see the paramedic inserting an IV line to give me morphine, I was in so much agony that I couldn&#039;t talk or move &ndash; and that&rsquo;s when panic hit me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Skye managed to draw on her remaining strength to lift up her arm and the paramedic spotted her Medic Alert bracelet on her wrist and no morphine was given.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While I was left to recover from serious injuries from the attack, I have no doubt that my bracelet saved my life that night &ndash; and I wear it every hour of every day, because something can happen in an instant and it could be my only chance of survival.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Skye-Anne Ellard',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-08-22 13:56:36','2016-10-01 03:58:03','2016-10-01 13:27:51'),(92,168,4,0,104,'Thomas Bunning',NULL,NULL,'thomas-bunning',0,'Adelaide, SA, member since ','As someone who deeply understands the importance of being able to communicate clearly, it&rsquo;s great to know that even if I was caught in an emergency overseas, my medical details would be made available to the people treating me.','<p>MedicAlert Foundation member Tom Bunning was walking a familiar stretch of road when disaster struck. In the early hours of Sunday 3 September 2006 Tom was hit by a passing car, leaving the then 19-year-old unconscious and fighting for his life.</p>\r\n<p>With a punctured lung and severe swelling of the brain, amongst other injuries, Tom was left in an induced coma and on life-support.</p>\r\n<p>After a week and just as things seemed on the up, Tom suffered another set back, with massive and unrelieved pressure on the brain causing further damage and leaving doctors with little hope.</p>\r\n<p>To save his life surgeons were forced to perform a bifrontal craniectomy &ndash; removing a large flap of skull to reduce the pressure on his brain. While the procedure was successful, Tom was given slim to no chance of survival, as doctors warned of what his life might be like even if he did wake up.</p>\r\n<p>After 3 weeks in a coma, he started to breathe on his own and his brain began to settle. Over the coming weeks and months, Tom&rsquo;s family were given the shocking news that a third of his brain was dead. But still he endured, and as he woke up to realise he couldn&rsquo;t walk, talk, read, write, understand what people said, remember or even taste, it was evident that Tom&rsquo;s life would never be the same again.</p>\r\n<p>Nine years on and Tom&rsquo;s will to live life to the fullest has seen him fight to regain much of what he lost, including re-enrolling in university, travelling the world and becoming the Co-Chair of &lsquo;Talkback&rsquo; which is the peak body for people living with aphasia in South Australia.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Aphasia is a loss of language skills caused by stroke or other brain injury and continues to be one of the greatest challenges in my life,&rdquo; Tom says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In South Australia there are about 10,000 people living with aphasia, and yet it remains a very misunderstood and unknown disorder, largely because those with it struggle to communicate.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>As someone with a number of complex and potentially life-threatening conditions, Tom says a MedicAlert membership was a simple choice that gave both he and his mum peace of mind.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t want to have to stop doing the things I loved, like travel, study and attending social outings, but I also knew that I would be in danger if an emergency struck and the people around me weren&rsquo;t aware of my medical history,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As someone who deeply understands the importance of being able to communicate clearly, it&rsquo;s great to know that even if I was caught in an emergency overseas, my medical details would be made available to the people treating me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Tom says he is looking forward to an upcoming trip to Europe, and feels that extra layer of confidence knowing that the MedicAlert emblem is recognised worldwide.</p>\r\n<p>To find out more about the Talkback Association for Aphasia head to <a href=&quot;http://www.aphasia.asn.au/&quot;>http://www.aphasia.asn.au/</a></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Thomas Bunning',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/thomas_bunning.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-08-19 10:02:45','2016-10-10 00:35:32',NULL),(93,173,4,0,104,'Skye-Anne Ellard',NULL,NULL,'skye-anne-ellard',0,'Seaford Rise, SA, member since 2009','Never having had morphine before I was looking forward to the near-instant pain relief that had been promised to me, but what I got was certainly unexpected and nowhere near that outcome','<p>As a result of being born prematurely, Skye-Anne Ellard suffered from recurring kidney problems from a young age - and over the years that followed she became very familiar with the hospital system.</p>\r\n<p>As it turns out those experiences must have left their mark, because the now 23-year old Adelaide careworker has turned her attention to carving a career in the health sector, and is currently studying nursing at Flinders University.</p>\r\n<p>It wasn&rsquo;t until her early teens, however, that she stumbled across the fact that she has a severe &ndash; and potentially fatal &ndash; anaphylaxis to morphine. It was when she was admitted to hospital as a 16-year old with a severe kidney infection and given morphine to better manage the crippling pain that the drama began.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Never having had morphine before I was looking forward to the near-instant pain relief that had been promised to me, but what I got was certainly unexpected and nowhere near that outcome,&rdquo; Skye says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As soon as the needle had been pushed into my IV I could feel the morphine moving into my vein and my body suddenly felt like it was on fire, with a horrific rash instantly spreading,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My throat started to close up, I couldn&#039;t breathe, and the last thing I remembered before passing out was an alarm beeping, people running from all directions towards my room, and my mum being pushed out of the way.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The emergency response was justified, with Skye going into respiratory arrest and having to be intubated and given shots of adrenaline to get her heart back to beating in a normal rhythm.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;When I woke up a few hours later the doctor told me it was the quickest and worst reaction to morphine that he had ever seen - so for my own piece of mind I became a Medic Alert member and invested in a bracelet,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>After already surviving one near-miss, the decision to become a Medic Alert member was one that would save her life several years later.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I had been out at a music festival at Glenelg and was walking with some friends when we were jumped and bashed in the middle of a busy street,&rdquo; Skye says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;After being knocked to the ground, repeatedly punched in the head and kicked to the back of my skull and ribs I was barely conscious when an ambulance arrived.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The paramedics put me in a spinal collar and strapped me to a board, and even though I could see the paramedic inserting an IV line to give me morphine, I was in so much agony that I couldn&#039;t talk or move &ndash; and that&rsquo;s when panic hit me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Skye managed to draw on her remaining strength to lift up her arm and the paramedic spotted her Medic Alert bracelet on her wrist and no morphine was given.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While I was left to recover from serious injuries from the attack, I have no doubt that my bracelet saved my life that night &ndash; and I wear it every hour of every day, because something can happen in an instant and it could be my only chance of survival.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Skye-Anne Ellard',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/skye_ellard.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-08-22 13:56:36','2016-10-10 00:35:25',NULL),(94,576,4,0,104,'Ella',NULL,NULL,'ella',0,'VIC, member since 2014','The MedicAlert School&rsquo;s Program is a great initiative because it doesn&rsquo;t just help to raise funds for the school, but also assist teachers to quickly identify a child&rsquo;s medical needs and take the right steps - especially when that child may not be able to speak and let them know what is wrong','<p>When it comes to being terrified of needles, Ella is just like every other 9-year old. Where she does differ to most of her friends is that her severe allergies to a range of foods and animals means that she not only has to carry an epi-pen with her at all times &ndash; that needle might very well save her life in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>It is an irony that is not lost on Ella&rsquo;s mother, Angela, who says that her daughter&rsquo;s severe allergies include eggs, nuts, bee and wasp stings, dog saliva, as well as horse and cat hair. In Ella&rsquo;s case, anaphylaxis can happen with just touching an allergen, not even ingesting it &ndash; all she has to do is hold a cashew and within 5 minutes she is fighting for her life.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;With such a broad range of allergies against a lot of things that most of us commonly encounter through our everyday lives it would be easy to wrap Ella in a bubble, but she is an active girl that enjoys a number of outdoor sports so we manage the risks as best we can,&rdquo; says mum Angela.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As well as basketball and swimming, Ella is active in athletics and cross country running &ndash; so she certainly hasn&rsquo;t shied away from getting out into nature, and we&rsquo;ve been very supportive of her every step of the way,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We recently decided to get Ella a MedicAlert bracelet because we recognise that as she gets older we cannot be with her every minute of every day, and you never know when an anaphylactic episode might suddenly happen.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Ella was only about 18 month&rsquo;s old when Angela discovered that her daughter had life-threatening allergies, and during the testing that followed they found that exposure to several different allergens at any one time posed an even more serious threat.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember introducing egg into her diet and hadn&rsquo;t even put it into her mouth when she suddenly broke out with welts on her face because it had just touched her skin &ndash; thankfully she hadn&rsquo;t ingested any of it,&rdquo; Angela says.</p>\r\n<p>That first anaphylactic reaction was to be followed by another 7 episodes in the years that followed.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember one morning going to the park before school, and Ella must have come in contact with an allergen because she suddenly had trouble breathing. I was only four blocks away from Geelong Hospital and was rushing to get her there when I knew that she was not going to make it, so I had to pull over and use an epi-pen on her,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>It was the launch the <a title=&quot;MedicAlert in Schools&quot; href=&quot;https://www.medicalert.org.au/schools/&quot;>MedicAlert Foundation&rsquo;s Schools Program</a> that prompted Angela to make Ella a member.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The MedicAlert School&rsquo;s Program is a great initiative because it doesn&rsquo;t just help to raise funds for the school, but also assist teachers to quickly identify a child&rsquo;s medical needs and take the right steps - especially when that child may not be able to speak and let them know what is wrong,&rdquo; Angela says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Everyone at Ella&rsquo;s school has been terrific and we have spoken with the school about her condition and helped to develop management plans should something happen. The school has responded really well, and in addition to removing trees that are known to attract bees, they have also supplied a bike for a teacher at school sporting events or cross country run to ensure a rapid response,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>Ella wears one of MedicAlert&rsquo;s versatile sports bands and has found that it doesn&rsquo;t impact on any of her sporting pursuits &ndash; and has in fact been granted special permission to wear it on court while playing basketball.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Her bracelet provides peace of mind, and means we don&rsquo;t have to worry as much over the little things like her riding a bike up and down the road, because we know if something happens and her throat closes over during an anaphylaxis that her MedicAlert emblem will speak on her behalf,&rdquo; Angela says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While you could never put a price on her life, making Ella a MedicAlert member and getting her a bracelet has been a good investment, and I would strongly encourage other parents who have children with similar conditions to do the same.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>More information about the MedicAlert Schools Program can be found at <a href=&quot;https://www.medicalert.org.au/schools/&quot;>https://www.medicalert.org.au/schools/</a></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Ella',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:28:35','2016-10-01 04:02:36','2016-10-01 13:32:24'),(95,576,4,0,104,'Ella',NULL,NULL,'ella',0,'VIC, member since 2014','The MedicAlert School&rsquo;s Program is a great initiative because it doesn&rsquo;t just help to raise funds for the school, but also assist teachers to quickly identify a child&rsquo;s medical needs and take the right steps - especially when that child may not be able to speak and let them know what is wrong','<p>When it com