bout her condition and helped to develop management plans should something happen. The school has responded really well, and in addition to removing trees that are known to attract bees, they have also supplied a bike for a teacher at school sporting events or cross country run to ensure a rapid response,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>Ella wears one of MedicAlert&rsquo;s versatile sports bands and has found that it doesn&rsquo;t impact on any of her sporting pursuits &ndash; and has in fact been granted special permission to wear it on court while playing basketball.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Her bracelet provides peace of mind, and means we don&rsquo;t have to worry as much over the little things like her riding a bike up and down the road, because we know if something happens and her throat closes over during an anaphylaxis that her MedicAlert emblem will speak on her behalf,&rdquo; Angela says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While you could never put a price on her life, making Ella a MedicAlert member and getting her a bracelet has been a good investment, and I would strongly encourage other parents who have children with similar conditions to do the same.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Ella',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/ella_partington.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:28:35','2016-10-10 00:06:41',NULL),(97,577,4,0,104,'Rachael C',NULL,NULL,'rachael-c',0,'Glen Waverley, VIC, member since 2012','I wear my bracelet all the time because it provides me with peace of mind, which I&rsquo;m grateful for because I never know what might trigger an episode','<p>Imagine being suddenly trapped in your own body, temporarily unable to communicate with those who have come to your aid, but still being fully aware of what is happening around you.</p>\r\n<p>That nightmare scenario has been the reality for 26-year old Rachael on several occasions as a result of a rare disorder which causes her to experience severe dissociative episodes where she appears unconscious but can hear and feel people.</p>\r\n<p>Adding to her challenges, the young Victorian supermarket worker also suffers from Chronic Fatigue Syndrome, and was diagnosed with epilepsy five years ago.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Thankfully I have only experienced one epileptic seizure over that time, but the same cannot be said when it comes to the number of dissociative episodes I&rsquo;ve experienced as part of having Dissociative Identity Disorder,&rdquo; Rachael says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember staying at a respite facility and having an episode three out of the four days there &ndash; the staff couldn&rsquo;t work out what was going on, or how to help.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In 2012 I was taken to hospital after another severe episode and was completely unresponsive for nearly 10 hours, unable to talk or tell anyone what was wrong &ndash; even though I could hear staff and feel them hurting me as they tried to work out what was happening.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>With such an uncommon condition, Rachael says she has had a number of doubters &ndash; including a few who have dismissed it as merely attention-grabbing behaviour &ndash; but the reality is far from that.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This disorder has landed me in difficult, embarrassing, and stressful situations a number of times, so I decided to get a MedicAlert bracelet because if I&rsquo;m not with someone who knows my condition and what to do, the bracelet will provide information when I can&rsquo;t speak,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I wear my bracelet all the time because it provides me with peace of mind, which I&rsquo;m grateful for because I never know what might trigger an episode.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While I have epilepsy as a physical condition, my primary reason to become a MedicAlert member was because of my mental illness &ndash; and I encourage others in similar situations to put any embarrassment they might feel aside and take proactive steps to ensure their own safety too,&rdquo; says Rachael.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Rachael C',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:33:42','2016-10-01 04:04:48','2016-10-01 13:34:36'),(98,577,4,0,104,'Rachael C',NULL,NULL,'rachael-c',0,'Glen Waverley, VIC, member since 2012','I wear my bracelet all the time because it provides me with peace of mind, which I&rsquo;m grateful for because I never know what might trigger an episode','<p>Imagine being suddenly trapped in your own body, temporarily unable to communicate with those who have come to your aid, but still being fully aware of what is happening around you.</p>\r\n<p>That nightmare scenario has been the reality for 26-year old Rachael on several occasions as a result of a rare disorder which causes her to experience severe dissociative episodes where she appears unconscious but can hear and feel people.</p>\r\n<p>Adding to her challenges, the young Victorian supermarket worker also suffers from Chronic Fatigue Syndrome, and was diagnosed with epilepsy five years ago.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Thankfully I have only experienced one epileptic seizure over that time, but the same cannot be said when it comes to the number of dissociative episodes I&rsquo;ve experienced as part of having Dissociative Identity Disorder,&rdquo; Rachael says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember staying at a respite facility and having an episode three out of the four days there &ndash; the staff couldn&rsquo;t work out what was going on, or how to help.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In 2012 I was taken to hospital after another severe episode and was completely unresponsive for nearly 10 hours, unable to talk or tell anyone what was wrong &ndash; even though I could hear staff and feel them hurting me as they tried to work out what was happening.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>With such an uncommon condition, Rachael says she has had a number of doubters &ndash; including a few who have dismissed it as merely attention-grabbing behaviour &ndash; but the reality is far from that.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This disorder has landed me in difficult, embarrassing, and stressful situations a number of times, so I decided to get a MedicAlert bracelet because if I&rsquo;m not with someone who knows my condition and what to do, the bracelet will provide information when I can&rsquo;t speak,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I wear my bracelet all the time because it provides me with peace of mind, which I&rsquo;m grateful for because I never know what might trigger an episode.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While I have epilepsy as a physical condition, my primary reason to become a MedicAlert member was because of my mental illness &ndash; and I encourage others in similar situations to put any embarrassment they might feel aside and take proactive steps to ensure their own safety too,&rdquo; says Rachael.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Rachael C',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/rachael_carter.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:33:42','2016-10-10 00:34:13',NULL),(99,578,4,0,104,'Kurt Byers',NULL,NULL,'kurt-byers',0,'Lavender Bay, NSW, member since 2012','I was struggling to speak and couldn&rsquo;t tell hospital staff what was wrong with me &ndash; but I was able to show them my MedicAlert emblem and they immediately gave me the right treatment for my condition','<p><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>Thankfully there aren&rsquo;t too many babies with a life-threatening allergy to their own mother&rsquo;s milk, but for NSW man Kurt Byers a severe dairy allergy has meant that he has to grow up avoiding all types of milk and dairy products or risk having an anaphylaxis reaction.</p>\r\n<p>The 35-year old, who works in the healthcare industry, says he has grown used to the daily threat of anaphylaxis where even the slightest exposure to dairy sees his throat swell and blood pressure drop to dangerous levels.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As a nine month old baby I was diagnosed with an allergy against all types of dairy products and I was five years old when I first became a MedicAlert member,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember wearing my emblem until I was in my teens, but among everything else going on in my life it no longer seemed an important part of risk management for my condition so I foolishly stopped wearing it and let my membership lapse. I thought I was a bullet-proof teenager who could take care of himself.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In hindsight it was one of the most dangerous decisions I could have made, especially because I have averaged at least one major reaction every year despite my best efforts to avoid all dairy products,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p>It was in late 2010 that Kurt had a reaction that nearly ended his life, and served as the spark to re-new his MedicAlert membership.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was at a work function and had a couple of sips of wine thinking I was safe, but I later found out that a dairy component is sometimes used during the production process, and that is what triggered my most sudden and near-fatal reaction. This was the first time I had encountered dairy products in wine, and I was completely unaware of the risk,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was rushed to hospital and was taken straight into the resuscitation area in the Emergency department. After being resuscitated I had a second (biphasic) reaction about 45 minutes after adrenaline had been administered. This was another severe reaction and it resulted in the emergency team having to resuscitate me for the second time in less than an hour.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That was the defining moment when I decided to take back control and started wearing my MedicAlert emblem again. It really scared me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Kurt says he now puts on his MedicAlert dog tag as part of his daily ritual, so that every time he leaves the house he has the added confidence that the distinctive emblem is there to provide information and talk for him during an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That decision has already paid off because it was only last year when I was at a function in Melbourne where during a dinner with clients I ate something with trace elements of dairy &ndash; which triggered an immediate reaction,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A colleague who knew about my allergy rushed me to hospital but because she wasn&rsquo;t a family member she wasn&rsquo;t allowed into the emergency area. I was struggling to speak and couldn&rsquo;t tell hospital staff what was wrong with me. While they knew it was some sort of reaction they didn&rsquo;t know why &ndash; but I was able to show them my MedicAlert emblem and they immediately gave me the right treatment for my condition.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Kurt says his own experiences should serve as a warning to others with life-threatening allergies to not be complacent about their own health and safety.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I urge young teens &ndash; especially men &ndash; with a condition like mine to make it a priority to wear a MedicAlert emblem and stay a member. There is now a range of bracelet and necklace options available and I have opted for a dog tag because it is discreet and can be worn under my work clothing,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have greater control over my own safety at home, but as soon as I step outside my MedicAlert is around my neck because I know that while I am excessively careful on what I eat or drink there is always the risk that I could be exposed to dairy and I have a lot more living that I want to do.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Kurt Byers',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:35:16','2016-10-01 04:06:33','2016-10-01 13:36:21'),(100,578,4,0,104,'Kurt Byers',NULL,NULL,'kurt-byers',0,'Lavender Bay, NSW, member since 2012','I was struggling to speak and couldn&rsquo;t tell hospital staff what was wrong with me &ndash; but I was able to show them my MedicAlert emblem and they immediately gave me the right treatment for my condition','<p><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>Thankfully there aren&rsquo;t too many babies with a life-threatening allergy to their own mother&rsquo;s milk, but for NSW man Kurt Byers a severe dairy allergy has meant that he has to grow up avoiding all types of milk and dairy products or risk having an anaphylaxis reaction.</p>\r\n<p>The 35-year old, who works in the healthcare industry, says he has grown used to the daily threat of anaphylaxis where even the slightest exposure to dairy sees his throat swell and blood pressure drop to dangerous levels.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As a nine month old baby I was diagnosed with an allergy against all types of dairy products and I was five years old when I first became a MedicAlert member,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember wearing my emblem until I was in my teens, but among everything else going on in my life it no longer seemed an important part of risk management for my condition so I foolishly stopped wearing it and let my membership lapse. I thought I was a bullet-proof teenager who could take care of himself.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In hindsight it was one of the most dangerous decisions I could have made, especially because I have averaged at least one major reaction every year despite my best efforts to avoid all dairy products,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p>It was in late 2010 that Kurt had a reaction that nearly ended his life, and served as the spark to re-new his MedicAlert membership.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was at a work function and had a couple of sips of wine thinking I was safe, but I later found out that a dairy component is sometimes used during the production process, and that is what triggered my most sudden and near-fatal reaction. This was the first time I had encountered dairy products in wine, and I was completely unaware of the risk,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was rushed to hospital and was taken straight into the resuscitation area in the Emergency department. After being resuscitated I had a second (biphasic) reaction about 45 minutes after adrenaline had been administered. This was another severe reaction and it resulted in the emergency team having to resuscitate me for the second time in less than an hour.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That was the defining moment when I decided to take back control and started wearing my MedicAlert emblem again. It really scared me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Kurt says he now puts on his MedicAlert dog tag as part of his daily ritual, so that every time he leaves the house he has the added confidence that the distinctive emblem is there to provide information and talk for him during an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That decision has already paid off because it was only last year when I was at a function in Melbourne where during a dinner with clients I ate something with trace elements of dairy &ndash; which triggered an immediate reaction,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A colleague who knew about my allergy rushed me to hospital but because she wasn&rsquo;t a family member she wasn&rsquo;t allowed into the emergency area. I was struggling to speak and couldn&rsquo;t tell hospital staff what was wrong with me. While they knew it was some sort of reaction they didn&rsquo;t know why &ndash; but I was able to show them my MedicAlert emblem and they immediately gave me the right treatment for my condition.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Kurt says his own experiences should serve as a warning to others with life-threatening allergies to not be complacent about their own health and safety.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I urge young teens &ndash; especially men &ndash; with a condition like mine to make it a priority to wear a MedicAlert emblem and stay a member. There is now a range of bracelet and necklace options available and I have opted for a dog tag because it is discreet and can be worn under my work clothing,&rdquo; Kurt says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have greater control over my own safety at home, but as soon as I step outside my MedicAlert is around my neck because I know that while I am excessively careful on what I eat or drink there is always the risk that I could be exposed to dairy and I have a lot more living that I want to do.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Kurt Byers',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/kurt_byers.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:35:16','2016-10-10 00:32:53',NULL),(101,579,4,0,104,'Alan M',NULL,NULL,'alan-m',0,'Five Dock, NSW, member since 2008','Language barriers could cause real problems. My MedicAlert gives me great comfort that local medical personnel anywhere will recognise my emblem and can call the 24/7 hotline if they need more information about me or my medication','<p>Happily retired, Alan returned from an overseas trip five years ago with a swollen leg. Tests revealed that his blood clots at a faster rate that normal making him susceptible to a deep vein thrombosis (DVT). A DVT is a blood clot that forms in the deep veins of the leg putting him at risk of pulmonary embolism, which can be fatal. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;As I frequently travel overseas, I now take a daily dose of Warfarin to reduce the risk of blood clots forming,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;It really doesn&rsquo;t affect my everyday life other than needing to have regular blood tests to monitor its effects and make sure the dose is right.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> However, the most common side effect of Warfarin is bleeding, particularly when injured. Alan&rsquo;s GP suggested he wear a MedicAlert emblem to ensure that paramedics and medical personnel were aware of his medication. He now has both a necklace and bracelet. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;I remember going into a pharmacy overseas to buy some sea sickness tablets before taking a ferry,&rdquo; Alan says. &ldquo;But when I showed the pharmacist my MedicAlert ID, she advised that none of the over-the-counter products were compatible with Warfarin.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> &ldquo;On another occasion in Italy, I unexpectedly ran out of my medication. Thanks to my emblem, the pharmacist was able to dispense the medication to tide me over during my travels. It&rsquo;s also very useful when I need to have blood tests while away.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> Alan believes that his MedicAlert emblem provides not only practical everyday support, but is also a vital backup should he have an unexpected accident. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;Language barriers could cause real problems. My MedicAlert gives me great comfort that local medical personnel anywhere will recognise my emblem and can call the 24/7 hotline if they need more information about me or my medication.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Alan M',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:37:31','2016-10-01 04:08:23','2016-10-01 13:38:11'),(102,579,4,0,104,'Alan M',NULL,NULL,'alan-m',0,'Five Dock, NSW, member since 2008','Language barriers could cause real problems. My MedicAlert gives me great comfort that local medical personnel anywhere will recognise my emblem and can call the 24/7 hotline if they need more information about me or my medication','<p>Happily retired, Alan returned from an overseas trip five years ago with a swollen leg. Tests revealed that his blood clots at a faster rate that normal making him susceptible to a deep vein thrombosis (DVT). A DVT is a blood clot that forms in the deep veins of the leg putting him at risk of pulmonary embolism, which can be fatal. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;As I frequently travel overseas, I now take a daily dose of Warfarin to reduce the risk of blood clots forming,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;It really doesn&rsquo;t affect my everyday life other than needing to have regular blood tests to monitor its effects and make sure the dose is right.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> However, the most common side effect of Warfarin is bleeding, particularly when injured. Alan&rsquo;s GP suggested he wear a MedicAlert emblem to ensure that paramedics and medical personnel were aware of his medication. He now has both a necklace and bracelet. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;I remember going into a pharmacy overseas to buy some sea sickness tablets before taking a ferry,&rdquo; Alan says. &ldquo;But when I showed the pharmacist my MedicAlert ID, she advised that none of the over-the-counter products were compatible with Warfarin.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> &ldquo;On another occasion in Italy, I unexpectedly ran out of my medication. Thanks to my emblem, the pharmacist was able to dispense the medication to tide me over during my travels. It&rsquo;s also very useful when I need to have blood tests while away.&rdquo; <br /> <br /> Alan believes that his MedicAlert emblem provides not only practical everyday support, but is also a vital backup should he have an unexpected accident. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;Language barriers could cause real problems. My MedicAlert gives me great comfort that local medical personnel anywhere will recognise my emblem and can call the 24/7 hotline if they need more information about me or my medication.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Alan M',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/alan_mingo.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 13:37:31','2016-10-09 23:43:30',NULL),(103,10,1,0,0,'Terms and Conditions',NULL,NULL,'terms-and-conditions',1,'<div style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>\r\n<p><em>1. General</em></p>\r\n<p>1.1 The MedicAlert Foundation site at http://www.medicalert.org.au (&ldquo;<strong>the Site</strong>&rdquo;) is a website where people can browse, apply for Membership of MedicAlert Foundation and then select and order products from Australia Medic Alert Foundation ACN 050 542 455 (&ldquo;<strong>Foundation</strong>&rdquo;, &ldquo;<strong>us</strong>&rdquo; or &ldquo;<strong>we</strong>&rdquo;).</p>\r\n<p>1.2 Your access to and use of the Site, including the placing of an order for Products through the Site, is governed by these Terms and Conditions. You must be a Member of the Foundation to order Products from us.</p>\r\n<p>1.3 In these Terms and Conditions, Member Personal Information and Member Medical Information and any updates of that information are together referred to as &ldquo;<strong>Member Information</strong>&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p><em>2. Terms and Conditions for the Use of this Site</em></p>\r\n<p>2.1 You agree to be bound by, and comply with, these Terms and Conditions, by accessing and/or using the Site.</p>\r\n<p>2.2 You agree to comply with all relevant laws relating to your use of the Site and any order you place through the Site.</p>\r\n<p>2.3 You agree not to access, copy or use any data listed on or available through the Site except for the purpose of using the Site.</p>\r\n<p><em>3. Your Account (online only)</em></p>\r\n<p>3.1 To access and use the full functionality of the Site, you will be required to create a unique user account with an access password (&quot;<strong>Account</strong>&quot;). You are responsible for maintaining the confidentiality of your Account and associated password, and for restricting access to your computer. You are responsible for all activities that occur on your Account or as a result of the use of your password.</p>\r\n<p>3.2 You must be aged 18 or over to order Products from the Foundation. By submitting an order, you warrant and represent to the Foundation that you are aged 18 years or older.</p>\r\n<p>3.3 The Foundation reserves the right to refuse service, terminate Accounts, remove or edit content, or cancel orders in its sole discretion, at any time and with immediate effect.</p>\r\n<p><em>4. Applications for Membership</em></p>\r\n<p>4.1 You must be aged 18 years or over to make an application for Membership of the Foundation (&quot;<strong>Application</strong>&quot;).</p>\r\n<p>4.2 If an Application for Membership of the Foundation is in respect of a person who is under the age of 18, the Application must be made and submitted by the parent or guardian of that person.</p>\r\n<p>4.3 It is a requirement for a valid Application for Membership that you provide all of the Member Information which is requested on the Site.</p>\r\n<p><em>5. Provision and Use of Member Information</em></p>\r\n<p>5.1 You acknowledge that the Member Personal Information and the Member Medical Information set out in the Application is accurate and complete at the date of making the Application.</p>\r\n<p>5.2 You acknowledge and agree that the Foundation:</p>\r\n<p>a) is entitled to rely on the completeness and accuracy of the Member Information;</p>\r\n<p>b) has no responsibility to verify or authenticate the Member Information;</p>\r\n<p>c) recommends that you obtain authentication of the accuracy of the Member Medical Information from your (or the applicant&rsquo;s, as relevant) authorised healthcare provider; and</p>\r\n<p>d) reserves the right to request you to have your (or the applicant&#039;s, as relevant) healthcare provider authenticate the accuracy of the Member Medical Information at your/the applicant&#039;s cost.</p>\r\n<p>5.3 You acknowledge that it is your responsibility:</p>\r\n<p>a) to immediately advise the Foundation of any change in the Member Information;</p>\r\n<p>b) to check the Member Information recorded on the Member emblem/Membership card; and</p>\r\n<p>c) to advise the Foundation immediately if you become aware that the Member Information is incomplete or inaccurate whether or not the Member Information has been authenticated by a healthcare provider.</p>\r\n<p>5.4 If the Foundation requests you to obtain authentication of the accuracy of the Member Information from a healthcare provider the Foundation is entitled to rely on the accuracy of the Member Information provided until such authentication is received.</p>\r\n<p>5.5 You acknowledge and agree that the Member Information will be entered into the Foundation&rsquo;s database and that the Foundation will not retain a hard copy of the Application submitted.</p>\r\n<p>5.6 You authorise the Foundation to release the Member Information to a healthcare provider or emergency services personnel in a medical or other emergency. The Foundation will use its best endeavours to verify that the person requesting the information is a healthcare provider or emergency services personnel who require immediate access to the Member Information in circumstances where you (or the Member, if you are applying on behalf of another person) are unable to provide it.</p>\r\n<p>5.7 Without limiting any other provisions of these Terms and Conditions, you release the Foundation from any claim by you or for any liability:</p>\r\n<p>a) for loss or damage sustained by you or any other person, arising directly or indirectly as a result of the provision of the Member Information to any person or organisation, if the Member Information is incomplete or inaccurate or out of date due to any act or omission on your part; or</p>\r\n<p>b) if the Member Information is provided to a person or organisation without your consent, provided that the Foundation has reasonable grounds for believing that it was in your interest for the Member Information to be released to that person or organisation, in accordance with our Privacy Policy.</p>\r\n<p>5.8 If you are making an Application as the parent or guardian of the Member, any reference to &quot;<strong>you</strong>&quot; or &quot;<strong>your</strong>&quot; in this document is also a reference to the Member unless the context otherwise requires, and you warrant and represent that you are authorised to complete the Application on behalf of the Member and that the information provided is complete and accurate. You agree to indemnify and keep indemnified the Foundation from and against any cost, claim, loss or damage suffered by the Foundation either directly or indirectly as a result of the breach by you of this warranty.</p>\r\n<p><em>6. Use of Foundation Products</em></p>\r\n<p>6.1 The release of the Member Information to a healthcare provider or emergency services personnel in a medical or other emergency depends on the healthcare provider or emergency services personnel being aware of your Membership emblem.</p>\r\n<p>6.2 You will find information on the Site about how you should wear or display your Membership emblem. It is important that you follow those recommendations. The Foundation devotes considerable effort to promoting awareness amongst healthcare providers and emergency services personnel that in an emergency situation they should check the wrist or neck of a person for evidence of Membership of the Foundation. If the Membership emblem is not displayed in accordance with the recommendations of the Foundation it will greatly reduce the likelihood that the emblem will come to the attention of a healthcare provider or emergency services personnel in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>6.3 While the Foundation uses all reasonable endeavours to promote and continue awareness of the Foundation amongst healthcare providers and emergency services personnel it does not warrant that even if a Membership emblem is worn in accordance with the recommendations on the Site, it will in every emergency situation be detected by the relevant personnel.</p>\r\n<p><em>7. Annual Members - Service Fee &amp; Information Update</em></p>\r\n<p>7.1 If you are an Annual Member, an annual service fee payable by you, commencing on the date of your Membership joining date. The Foundation will set the amount of the fee in its discretion and the preferred payment methods are BPay and Direct Debit. We also accept Visa, Mastercard, cheque or money order. Each year you will receive an Annual Renewal Notice setting out the amount payable by you to maintain your Membership, the payment methods available and a copy of your Member Information held on file. This is the time to review all of your details for accuracy and inform the Foundation of any changes required. If you do not pay the fee due and payable by you to the Foundation and confirm or update the information held by the Foundation in respect of you, the Foundation will no longer consider you to be a Member of the Foundation, and will take all necessary steps to delete the Member Information it holds in respect of you. The Foundation will use its reasonable endeavours to notify you of any imminent deletion of the records and information it holds in respect of you, to give you a final opportunity to re-commence Membership, but you understand, acknowledge and agree that the Foundation is under no obligation to do so, and can delete the information it holds about you without further notice.</p>\r\n<p>7.2 The Terms and Conditions applicable to obtaining and maintaining Membership of the Foundation and/or use of the Site may be changed by the Foundation without notice, and such amendments will be effective from the date specified by the Foundation. Submission of an application for Membership, and payment of your annual Member service fee, is acceptance of these Terms and Conditions as varied from time to time.</p>\r\n<p><em>8. Life Members - Information Update</em></p>\r\n<p>8.1 If you are a Life Member, each year you will receive a copy of your Member Information held on file. This is the time to review all of your details for accuracy and inform the Foundation of any changes required. If you do not contact the Foundation every year to confirm the accuracy or update the information held by the Foundation in respect of you, the Foundation will no longer consider you to be a Member of the Foundation, and will take all necessary steps to delete the Member Information it holds in respect of you. The Foundation will use its reasonable endeavours to notify you of any imminent deletion of the records and information it holds in respect of you, to give you a final opportunity to re-commence Membership and status as a Life Member, but you understand, acknowledge and agree that the Foundation is under no obligation to do so, and can delete the information it holds about you without further notice.</p>\r\n<p>8.2 If you are a Life Member and require your information to be updated by the Foundation, a small administrative fee will be payable (the precise amount will be specified in our correspondence). Payment should accompany the form indicating the required changes.</p>\r\n<p>8.3 The Terms and Conditions applicable to obtaining and maintaining Membership of the Foundation as a Life Member and/or use of the Site may be changed by the Foundation without notice, and such amendments will be effective from the date specified by the Foundation. Confirming or updating the Member Information held by the Foundation about you is regarded as your acceptance of these Terms and Conditions as varied from time to time.</p>\r\n<p><em>9. Placing an order for Products</em></p>\r\n<p>9.1 You may order Products by submitting your order in accordance with these Terms and Conditions.</p>\r\n<p>9.2 Any order placed for a Product (whether through this Site, by placing a telephone order or returning a completed order form) is an offer by you to purchase the particular Product for the price notified (including the delivery and other charges and taxes) at the time you place the order, which can be accepted or rejected by the Foundation as specified in clause 10 below. Orders will not be processed and accepted by the Foundation unless and until payment is received in full.</p>\r\n<p>9.3 We may ask you to provide additional details or require you to confirm your details to enable us to process any orders placed.</p>\r\n<p>9.4 You agree to provide us with current, complete and accurate details in connection with each order you submit.</p>\r\n<p><em>10. Acceptance or rejection of an order</em></p>\r\n<p>10.1 We will accept or reject orders in our discretion. If we accept an order, this results in a separate binding agreement between you and the Foundation for the supply of those Products requested in your order, on these Terms and Conditions to the exclusion of all others. For each order accepted by us, we will:</p>\r\n<p>a) supply the Products to you in accordance with these Terms and Conditions; and</p>\r\n<p>b) for orders placed via the Site, we will send you an automated email confirmation of that order &ndash; though with the nature of the internet we cannot guarantee that you will receive this. Please add the Foundation email address (orders@medicalert.org.au) to your contact address book to ensure emails are not sent to your junk email folder, or blocked by your fire wall or other security settings.</p>\r\n<p>10.2 In certain circumstances, the Foundation may reject your order. Rejection of an order is in the Foundation&#039;s absolute discretion, for reasons including but not limited to the Product not being available or if there is an error in the price or the Product description posted on the Site.</p>\r\n<p>10.3 If we are unable to accept an order, then we will endeavour to notify you of that at the time you place the order or within a reasonable time afterwards. We may in our discretion invite you to submit an order for an alternative Product, in which case clauses 9 and 10 will apply to your new order.</p>\r\n<p><em>11. Delivery of Products</em></p>\r\n<p>We deliver Products Australia-wide using Australia Post&#039;s standard delivery services (unless specified otherwise). Products valued over $160 are generally sent via Australia Post&#039;s registered post service (some exclusions apply). Please allow approximately 20 working days for delivery using Australia Post&#039;s standard delivery services. Other timeframes for delivery will apply if delivery method is different. We only deliver Products ordered to addresses in Australia. If you require delivery to an international address, please contact us to arrange this.</p>\r\n<p><em>12. Cancelling an order</em></p>\r\n<p>12.1 We may cancel any part of an order (including any orders that we have accepted) without any liability to you for that cancellation at any time prior to delivery of Products to you if:</p>\r\n<p>a) the Products are not available; or</p>\r\n<p>b) there is an error in the price or the product description for the Product; or</p>\r\n<p>c) that we reasonably believe your order has been placed in breach of these Terms and Conditions.</p>\r\n<p>If we do so, then we will endeavour to provide you with reasonable notice of that cancellation, provide you with a suitable alternative Product, and will not charge you for the cancelled order (and will refund any payment you have made to us).</p>\r\n<p>12.2 Subject to clause 12.3, you may cancel an order by contacting Membership Services during Business Hours within 24 hours of placing your order. Upon cancelling the order, the Foundation will refund your payment either to your original payment method or through an alternative means selected by us, less an administration fee of $20.00. You cannot otherwise cancel an order.</p>\r\n<p>12.3 Orders for customised Products cannot be cancelled by you once the Product is in the manufacturing stage.</p>\r\n<p><em>13. Refunds / Returns</em></p>\r\n<p>13.1 Please choose carefully as the Foundation does not offer refunds for products as they are customised to individual requirements, unless there is a valid claim under the Product Warranty, or the Foundation is required to do so by applicable law.</p>\r\n<p>13.2 If the Products supplied are defective in breach of the warranty set out in clause 14 below we will offer you an exchange, credit or refund, as per the Product Warranty terms.</p>\r\n<p>13.3 Memberships are non-transferable.</p>\r\n<p><em>14. Product Warranty</em></p>\r\n<p>14.1 We provide the warranty set out in Annexure A in respect of our Products (&quot;<strong>Product Warranty</strong>&quot;).</p>\r\n<p><em>15. Product pricing, fees and charges</em></p>\r\n<p>15.1 We will charge you, and you agree to pay, the purchase price of each Product that is ordered, the delivery fee for your order that we notify to you when you place your order