y concerned production crew and producer &ndash; but thankfully I was wearing my Medic Alert bracelet, so the ambulance crew could immediately read that I have diabetes and treat me with a dextrose infusion.','<p>For Courtney Young, the opportunity to watch the filming of The Price is Right promised to be an event to remember &ndash; especially if luck was on her side and she was picked to play the game.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It was in July 2013 that I made the trip to Sydney to visit my brother, and having also been invited as an audience member of the game show just added to the excitement,&rdquo; Courtney says.</p>\r\n<p>But that excitement quickly disappeared when the 28-year old suddenly collapsed during filming.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have Type 1 Diabetes and Gastoparesis, which is a rare condition where your stomach doesn&#039;t digest food properly &ndash; and with recording only expected to take about an hour and a half I had made the decision to hold off on eating until after it had ended to avoid being sick,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The audience wasn&rsquo;t allowed to bring in any food or drink, and production delays meant filming didn&rsquo;t actually start until 6pm, and by that stage my sugar levels were starting to drop.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Feeling the early signs of hypoglycaemia, Courtney remained hopeful that it would not escalate before she had a chance to treat it &ndash; but she suddenly passed out, much to the surprise of fellow audience members who thought she had just fallen asleep.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;All I can remember is waking up to ambulance officers standing over me, a completely empty studio and a very concerned production crew and producer &ndash; but thankfully I was wearing my Medic Alert bracelet, so the ambulance crew could immediately read that I have diabetes and treat me with a dextrose infusion,&rdquo; Courtney says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In talking to the paramedics it was reassuring to hear them say that they always look for a medical ID &ndash; so while I didn&rsquo;t end up winning anything on the game show, I was still a winner because I was wearing my Medic Alert bracelet.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>That wasn&rsquo;t the first time that the Queenslander, who is currently studying a degree in social work, has had a hypoglycaemic episode which has been mistaken for something else by a passer-by.</p>\r\n<p>It was during Schoolie celebrations in 2003 that she also suddenly collapsed, with onlookers and responding paramedics initially jumping to the conclusion that it was alcohol-related.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That incident cemented the decision for me to become a Medic Alert member so that I can always have my bracelet to inform paramedics and others coming to my aid that I have these medical conditions,&rdquo; Courtney says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Now my bracelet gives me a voice, even if I am unconscious, and it gives me peace of mind that it is always there to talk for me when I am not able to talk for myself,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d urge anyone with a life-threatening medical condition to make the investment and become a Medic Alert member - because when it comes to protecting your life, the small outlay is always going to be a price that is right!&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Courtney Young',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:42:36','2016-10-01 05:13:48','2016-10-01 14:43:36'),(119,585,4,0,104,'Courtney Young',NULL,NULL,'courtney-young',0,'Beenleigh, QLD, member since 2003','All I can remember is waking up to ambulance officers standing over me, a completely empty studio and a very concerned production crew and producer &ndash; but thankfully I was wearing my Medic Alert bracelet, so the ambulance crew could immediately read that I have diabetes and treat me with a dextrose infusion.','<p>For Courtney Young, the opportunity to watch the filming of The Price is Right promised to be an event to remember &ndash; especially if lu