), Abigail (9) and Samuel (7) from Western Australia says she decided to make her children MedicAlert members through the recently-launched School&rsquo;s Program and take advantage of the fact that the distinctive emblem is recognised around the world.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We live in a small rural Western Australia town of just 250 people and if one of my children has a meltdown and runs away they are relatively safe because they really don&rsquo;t have anywhere to go, and everyone knows who they are &ndash; but that isn&rsquo;t the case when we are abroad,&rdquo; Sharon says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The biggest risk we have is the danger of one of them feeling overwhelmed and becoming separated from us, which could happen over something very minor that probably wouldn&rsquo;t upset most other children,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our eldest son previously went on a church camp in Perth in Summer, and after becoming upset he ran off and ended up running onto a multi-lane highway and had to be restrained for his own safety and the police were called.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My younger son sometimes cannot speak when he gets upset, which means that he cannot tell someone his name or anything about himself, so the MedicAlert emblem becomes a voice on his behalf.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My daughter curls into a ball when she feels overwhelmed, and may make unusual noises to calm herself (imitating a phone ringing, or bird calls). These could be very confusing actions for someone who doesn&rsquo;t know Anna, but her MedicAlert bracelet will give them the information they need to obtain help for her.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Sharon said she had considered other options, but was attracted to the 24/7 hotline offered by MedicAlert, which allows responders to call and access other medical history and information about the wearer from anywhere in the world.</p>\r\n<p>She has opted for all of her children to wear one of the MedicAlert&rsquo;s sports bracelets, which is secured using a Velcro strap and has a stainless steel emblem. On the rear, in addition to the MedicAlert hotline number, Sharon and her husband Jeff&rsquo;s mobile numbers are both shown, and readers are advised the wearer has autism.</p>\r\n<p>With an anaphylaxis to shellfish, Sharon is no stranger to MedicAlert and is a member in her own right after her last trip to the US saw her ending up in hospital after a reaction from eating seafood.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was recommended by my Australian doctor to contact MedicAlert and become a member, and because I am a bit of a worrier it is comforting to know that my children are also now wearing identification that police and other emergency services are trained to look for in an emergency,&rdquo; Sharon says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Any parent who has a child with asthma, autism, anaphylaxis or some other condition should consider contacting MedicAlert and finding out about its Schools Program because it offers a very practical solution and also gives an opportunity to help the school broaden its fundraising activities because MedicAlert makes a donation back to the school for every new member it generates.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My advice is to spend time speaking to MedicAlert about exactly what should be engraved onto the back of the emblem. The advice and guidance we received was invaluable in choosing the final information displayed.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Sharon Jackson',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:44:11','2016-10-01 05:15:42','2016-10-01 14:45:30'),(121,586,4,0,104,'Sharon Jackson',NULL,NULL,'sharon-jackson',0,'Cranbrook, WA, member since 2010','I was recommended by my Australian doctor to contact MedicAlert and become a member, and because I am a bit of a worrier it is comforting to know that my children are also now wearing identification that police and other emergency services are trained to look for in an emergency.','<p>Any parent who has ever gone on a 