ULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:44:11','2016-10-10 00:36:12',NULL),(122,587,4,0,104,'Hanna Smith',NULL,NULL,'hanna-smith',0,'Aberfoyle Park, SA, member since 2013','As a teenager I know that I am in the most dangerous age range for someone with severe allergies so I am super careful with what I eat.','<p>For 19-year old Hanna Smith, growing up watching other children eat a peanut butter sandwich was enough to make the youngster feel sick because she knew the reaction it would have on her to eat one like it.</p>\r\n<p>Hanna&rsquo;s parents discovered that she was allergic to nuts after eating peanut butter and from that time, Hanna went out of her way to avoid them. It was when she was seven years old that curiosity got the better of her and she was unwell after eating a small piece of toast with peanut butter and vowed to never try anything with nuts again.</p>\r\n<p>Hanna had her first serious anaphylactic reaction several years later, when the then ten-year old drank vanilla soy milk - with some frightening results.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I had tried it many times before, but began coughing uncontrollably a short time later, prompting my mother to rush me to the hospital because she realised what was happening and could see that I was having difficulty breathing,&rdquo; Hanna says.</p>\r\n<p>Hanna&rsquo;s second anaphylactic reaction took place in December 2012 at a wedding reception.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The bride and groom were both Indian and I wasn&rsquo;t sure what food may have contained nuts, so I thought it best to play it safe and eat a small tuna cake, chicken, salad and some bread &ndash; but less than 30 minutes later I began coughing,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My anaphylaxis was so scary that from then just beginning to cough sets off panic in me, and while I can normally calm myself with a drink of water, that night I felt dizzy and drinking water wasn&rsquo;t helping.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Again, Hanna&rsquo;s mum came to the rescue and realised that she was experiencing an anaphylaxis and drove Hanna to hospital.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That time was even more severe than the first anaphylaxis and in addition to being covered in a rash I also couldn&rsquo;t stand or support my own weight,&rdquo; Hanna says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was taken through to resuscitation, and given my first shot of adrenaline, but with no improvement I was soon given a second and later a third injection and finally admitted for monitoring,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>That incident saw the teenager prescribed with two Epipens and advised to become a MedicAlert member.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As a teenager I know that I am in the most dangerous age range for someone with severe allergies so I am super careful with what I eat,&rdquo; Hanna says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t go to an Asian restaurant unless I contact them in advance to arrange my food, I avoid most chocolate and have become an expert at reading packets to find out whether I can eat certain foods,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I am glad that I wear a MedicAlert bracelet because I know it could save my life if I am unable to communicate.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Hanna Smith',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:46:06','2016-10-01 05:16:59','2016-10-01 14:46:47'),(123,587,4,0,104,'Hanna Smith',NULL,NULL,'hanna-smith',0,'Aberfoyle Park, SA, member since 2013','As a teenager I know that I am in the most dangerous age range for someone with severe allergies so I am super careful with what I eat.','<p>For 19-year old Hanna Smith, growing up watching other children eat a peanut butter sandwich was enough to make the youngster feel sick because she knew the reaction it would have on her to eat one like it.</p>\r\n<p>Hanna&rsquo;s parents discovered that she was allergic to nuts after eating peanut butter and from that time, Hanna went out of her way to avoid them. It was when she was seven years old that curiosity got the be