e have found that children in particular, are easy to educate about Bonnie&rsquo;s allergies, whereas adults have proven slightly harder to explain that a bad reaction could be life-threatening,&rdquo; Kathy says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It really was an easy decision to provide her with a MedicAlert bracelet because people are aware of what the emblem means and look for it. We did try other lesser-known options and they didn&rsquo;t last long and tended to blend in as more a fashion accessory. Whilst we have bought Bonnie a second MedicAlert bracelet as a back-up, it is still sitting untouched because her first bracelet is in perfect condition.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&quot;I strongly recommend investing in a MedicAlert bracelet to all parents who have children with allergies &ndash; the financial outlay is minimal, and the peace of mind it offers is priceless.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Kathy and Bonnie McAlinden',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/kathy_and_bonnie_mcalinden.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:48:46','2016-10-10 00:32:44',NULL),(128,590,4,0,104,'Fiona Smith',NULL,NULL,'fiona-smith',0,'Caversham, WA, member since 2007','I strongly encourage anyone with a bleeding disorder to become a member for that added peace of mind and be confident that a paramedic, doctor, nurse or some other health professional is aware of your condition.','<p>It wasn&rsquo;t until the birth of her son Liam, that Western Australia mother Fiona Smith, was diagnosed as having von Willebrand disorder.</p>\r\n<p>The rare bleeding disorder, estimated to occur in only 1-2 per cent of the population, is caused by a defect or deficiency of a blood clotting protein and can be inherited from either parent.</p>\r\n<p>The now 28-year old says it was on advice from her doctor that she first contacted MedicAlert Foundation to find out more about how to better protect herself &ndash; and she says that now offers her daily reassurance.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Even simple operations like having my wisdom teeth removed poses a significant risk, and while those planned events give me the opportunity to speak with doctors and medical staff and make them aware of my condition, I now feel a sense of relief in being prepared with the DDAVP drip,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I live an active life like anyone else, and like everyone else I could just as easily be suddenly injured in a car crash or experience some other accident where I may not be able to tell those coming to help me that I have this bleeding disorder.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Fiona says it is about managing the risks as best as she can and becoming a MedicAlert member was a proactive way for her to better protect herself.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have been rushed to hospital twice and on both occasions my MedicAlert membership has let the ambulance crew know immediately so they administer the right treatment,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I strongly encourage anyone with a bleeding disorder to become a member for that added peace of mind and be confident that a paramedic, doctor, nurse or some other health professional is aware of your condition.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;None of us knows that what life will throw at us every day, and that uncertainty means that becoming a MedicAlert member might one day save my life during a situation where I might have no control and cannot talk for myself,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I know of incidents where people with von Willebrand disorder have tragically died because emergency crews didn&rsquo;t know about their condition until it was too late, and I want to make sure that doesn&rsquo;t happen to me or my family,&rdquo; said Fiona.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Fiona Smith',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:50:08','2016-10-01 05:20:50','2016-10-01 14:50:38'),(129,590,4,0,104,'Fiona Smith',NULL,NULL,'fiona-smith',0,'Caversham, WA, member since 2007','I strongly encour