,0,104,'Lorraine Mulley',NULL,NULL,'lorraine-mulley',0,'Leumeah, NSW, member since 2011','I was very worried that I might mistakenly be put through an MRI if I was ever in an accident and my family couldn&#039;t be contacted, so wearing a MedicAlert emblem offers peace of mind should the worst happen.','<p>The old saying that &#039;an ounce of prevention is far better than a pound of cure&rsquo; certainly rings true for New South Wales woman Lorraine Mulley, who opted to invest in a MedicAlert membership after undergoing a cochlear implant several years ago.</p>\r\n<p>The 53-year old mother of three and professional deaf counsellor says the Sydney Cochlear Implant Centre recommended a MedicAlert bracelet after her operation because of the risk that the device would explode if she was subject to an MRI.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Despite coming from a very strong signing deaf family I had decided to wait for more than 30 years to have a Cochlear Implant because of the experimental nature of the surgery. Now that I have become one of the 5,000 Australians to receive an implant, it is now about best managing the risks that come with that decision,&rdquo; Lorraine says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was very worried that I might mistakenly be put through an MRI if I was ever in an accident and my family couldn&#039;t be contacted, so wearing a MedicAlert emblem offers peace of mind should the worst happen,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>As it turns out, Lorraine&rsquo;s MedicAlert bracelet recently proved its worth after she collapsed at work when she injured her leg.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My colleagues called the ambulance and stayed with me until the crew arrived. They also made sure the ambulance officers knew that I was wearing a MedicAlert bracelet and that I am deaf,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;On that occasion I had the help and support of people who knew me, but if something was to ever happen when I was alone or with strangers then I can be confident that my MedicAlert bracelet would provide life-saving information at a glance.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;And I have certainly not sacrificed fashion or fun in wearing a MedicAlert bracelet because I have a very nice gold one that I can wear on special occasions, and one that I have for everyday use.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Lorraine Mulley',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:52:55','2016-10-01 05:24:10','2016-10-01 14:53:58'),(133,592,4,0,104,'Lorraine Mulley',NULL,NULL,'lorraine-mulley',0,'Leumeah, NSW, member since 2011','I was very worried that I might mistakenly be put through an MRI if I was ever in an accident and my family couldn&#039;t be contacted, so wearing a MedicAlert emblem offers peace of mind should the worst happen.','<p>The old saying that &#039;an ounce of prevention is far better than a pound of cure&rsquo; certainly rings true for New South Wales woman Lorraine Mulley, who opted to invest in a MedicAlert membership after undergoing a cochlear implant several years ago.</p>\r\n<p>The 53-year old mother of three and professional deaf counsellor says the Sydney Cochlear Implant Centre recommended a MedicAlert bracelet after her operation because of the risk that the device would explode if she was subject to an MRI.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Despite coming from a very strong signing deaf family I had decided to wait for more than 30 years to have a Cochlear Implant because of the experimental nature of the surgery. Now that I have become one of the 5,000 Australians to receive an implant, it is now about best managing the risks that come with that decision,&rdquo; Lorraine says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was very worried that I might mistakenly be put through an MRI if I was ever in an accident and my family couldn&#039;t be contacted, so wearing a MedicAlert emblem offers peace of mind should the worst happen,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>As it turns out, Lorraine&rsquo;s MedicAlert bracelet recently proved its worth after she collapsed at work when she injured her leg.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;My colleagues called the ambulance and stayed with me until the crew arrived. They also made sure the ambulance officers knew that I was wearing a MedicAlert bracelet and that I am deaf,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;On that occasion I had the help and support of people who knew me, but if something was to ever happen when I was alone or with strangers then I can be confident that my MedicAlert bracelet would provide life-saving information at a glance.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;And I have certainly not sacrificed fashion or fun in wearing a MedicAlert bracelet because I have a very nice gold one that I can wear on special occasions, and one that I have for everyday use.&rdquo;</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Lorraine Mulley',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/lorraine_mulley.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:52:55','2016-10-10 00:33:02',NULL),(134,593,4,0,104,'Darren Pallot',NULL,NULL,'darren-pallot',0,'Margate, TAS, member since 2012','A critical day for me occurred when I had a reaction at work that saw my tongue and throat swell very quickly &ndash; so becoming a MedicAlert member was one proactive step towards keeping myself safe.','<p>The married father of four was unexpectedly diagnosed several years ago in his early 40s as having sensitivity to &lsquo;salicylates&rsquo; - derivatives of salicylic acid found in plants that act as a natural immune hormone and preservative to protect them against diseases, insects, fungi, and harmful bacteria.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember my tongue swelling up without warning which was pretty scary, so I made the decision to get behind the wheel and drive myself to hospital and only just made it in time,&rdquo; Darren says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;When the Doctor told me the reason for my reaction I didn&rsquo;t even know what salicylates were and was staggered at the idea that some of the foods I had been eating all my life had suddenly reached levels that were affecting my health.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I am more in tune with the signs that I am about to have a reaction now because I will start to get shaky, but others have been triggered by physical trauma without warning by something as simple as hitting my thumb with a hammer which then causes swelling in different parts of my body,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p>Salicylates are also found in many medications, perfumes and preservatives, and while both natural and synthetic salicylates can cause health problems in anyone when consumed in large doses, for those who are salicylate intolerant, even small doses can cause adverse reactions.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Completely eliminating salicylate from a diet and the environment is virtually impossible, so I had to put in place measures that best managed the risks and gave me a degree of control,&rdquo; Darren says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A critical day for me occurred when I had a reaction at work that saw my tongue and throat swell very quickly, and that got me thinking about what I would do if I couldn&rsquo;t talk and tell people what was happening &ndash; so becoming a MedicAlert member was one proactive step towards keeping myself safe.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have had a number of minor reactions in recent years, caused by anything from carrying a backpack of weed spray while gardening to taking nasal spray for hayfever, but three out of my four bad incidents have been triggered by sudden trauma,&rdquo; says Darren.</p>\r\n<p>Two of those serious incidents happened as a result of knee operations and Darren says wearing his stirling silver bracelet around his wrist is a visual warning for health professionals about his condition.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In addition to wearing my MedicAlert bracelet, I also now carry an EpiPen which also helps to give me peace of mind, knowing I have measures in place that will help during a reaction &ndash; especially if I cannot speak for myself.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Darren Pallot',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:54:37','2016-10-01 05:25:30','2016-10-01 14:55:18'),(135,593,4,0,104,'Darren Pallot',NULL,NULL,'darren-pallot',0,'Margate, TAS, member since 2012','A critical day for me occurred when I had a reaction at work that saw my tongue and throat swell very quickly &ndash; so becoming a MedicAlert member was one proactive step towards keeping myself safe.','<p>The married father of four was unexpectedly diagnosed several years ago in his early 40s as having sensitivity to &lsquo;salicylates&rsquo; - derivatives of salicylic acid found in plants that act as a natural immune hormone and preservative to protect them against diseases, insects, fungi, and harmful bacteria.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I remember my tongue swelling up without warning which was pretty scary, so I made the decision to get behind the wheel and drive myself to hospital and only just made it in time,&rdquo; Darren says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;When the Doctor told me the reason for my reaction I didn&rsquo;t even know what salicylates were and was staggered at the idea that some of the foods I had been eating all my life had suddenly reached levels that were affecting my health.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I am more in tune with the signs that I am about to have a reaction now because I will start to get shaky, but others have been triggered by physical trauma without warning by something as simple as hitting my thumb with a hammer which then causes swelling in different parts of my body,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n<p>Salicylates are also found in many medications, perfumes and preservatives, and while both natural and synthetic salicylates can cause health problems in anyone when consumed in large doses, for those who are salicylate intolerant, even small doses can cause adverse reactions.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Completely eliminating salicylate from a diet and the environment is virtually impossible, so I had to put in place measures that best managed the risks and gave me a degree of control,&rdquo; Darren says.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A critical day for me occurred when I had a reaction at work that saw my tongue and throat swell very quickly, and that got me thinking about what I would do if I couldn&rsquo;t talk and tell people what was happening &ndash; so becoming a MedicAlert member was one proactive step towards keeping myself safe.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have had a number of minor reactions in recent years, caused by anything from carrying a backpack of weed spray while gardening to taking nasal spray for hayfever, but three out of my four bad incidents have been triggered by sudden trauma,&rdquo; says Darren.</p>\r\n<p>Two of those serious incidents happened as a result of knee operations and Darren says wearing his stirling silver bracelet around his wrist is a visual warning for health professionals about his condition.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In addition to wearing my MedicAlert bracelet, I also now carry an EpiPen which also helps to give me peace of mind, knowing I have measures in place that will help during a reaction &ndash; especially if I cannot speak for myself.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Darren Pallot',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/testimonials/darren_pallot.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:54:37','2016-10-09 23:44:08',NULL),(136,594,4,0,104,'Judith Modistach',NULL,NULL,'judith-modistach',0,'Finnis, SA, member since 1978','I can&rsquo;t imagine going out without having my bracelet on. It&rsquo;s part of me.','<p>A major operation triggered a medical emergency for Judith who experienced a severe allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) after being given a common antibiotic during surgery.</p>\r\n<p>On her doctor&rsquo;s advice, Judith immediately joined the MedicAlert Foundation and has worn her stainless steel bracelet everyday since.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Together with details of my allergy, I also have my rare blood type engraved on my emblem as it&rsquo;s vital that I never receive my own blood type if I need a transfusion,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>Despite having angina, Judith leads a very active lifestyle dividing her time between weekly ten-pin bowling, part-time work and keeping up with two young grandchildren.</p>\r\n<p>She says the only time in the past 30 years she has taken her bracelet off, was when she lost it - and fortunately found it again, in the boot of her car.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t imagine going out without having my bracelet on. It&rsquo;s part of me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While my allergy and blood type are clearly flagged on my hospital and doctors&rsquo; files, in an emergency when I may be unable to speak for myself, my MedicAlert could literally be a lifesaver,&rdquo; Judith believes.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Judith Modistach',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-01 14:55:54','2016-10-01 05:26:41','2016-10-01 14:56:28'),(137,594,4,0,104,'Judith Modistach',NULL,NULL,'judith-modistach',0,'Finnis, SA, member since 1978','I can&rsquo;t imagine going out without having my bracelet on. It&rsquo;s part of me.','<p>A major operation triggered a medical emergency for Judith who experienced a severe allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) after being given a common antibiotic during surgery.</p>\r\n<p>On her doctor&rsquo;s advice, Judith immediately joined the MedicAlert Foundation and has worn her stainless steel bracelet everyday since.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Together with details of my allergy, I also have my rare blood type engraved on my emblem as it&rsquo;s vital that I never receive my own blood type if I need a transfusion,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>Despite having angina, Judith leads a very active lifestyle dividing her time between weekly ten-pin bowling, part-time work and keeping up with two young grandchildren.</p>\r\n<p>She says the only time in the past 30 years she has taken her bracelet off, was when she lost it - and fortunately found it again