'&#039;Time for Something New&#039; Competition Winners',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-05-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:22:47','2018-02-06 23:46:19',NULL),(160,602,2,0,17,'MedicAlert Foundation &lsquo;purple partnership&rsquo; helping Australians with epilepsy in March',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-foundation-andlsquopurple-partnershipandrsquo-helping-australians-with-epilepsy-in-march',0,'The month-long partnership with Epilepsy Australia that will see five dollars from every purple coloured MedicAlert medical ID sold during March donated to the organisation dedicated to helping ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>The month-long partnership with Epilepsy Australia that will see five dollars from every purple coloured MedicAlert medical ID sold during March donated to the organisation dedicated to helping Australians living with epilepsy, has started very positively.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, says it is pleasing to be able to support a fellow not-for-profit organisation and help to raise funds for Epilepsy Australia so it can continue to provide education, information and assistance to Australians living with epilepsy.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This is a way that lets our members play a role in helping to raise funds for a worthy cause by buying one of our new purple coloured medical IDs during the month of March,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;More than 400,000 Australians are believed to have epilepsy, and rather than focus our support just on the 26<sup>th</sup> March for Purple Day, we wanted to dedicate the entire month to encouraging people to wear a purple medical ID and help spread the word about epilepsy,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s also a way to add support to our many members who live with epilepsy and for them, knowing that should they have a sudden seizure then our distinctive emblem can speak for them &ndash; with their critical health information engraved and clearly visible on the back of their easily recognisable emblem,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner says the response from members so far this month has been extremely positive.</p>\r\n<p>As part of its service to members, MedicAlert Foundation provides a 24/7 hotline where emergency service personnel and healthcare professionals can access important additional medical and other details quickly and efficiently in a time of need.</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, Australia Medic Alert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service with close to 300,000 members joining since 1971.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation &lsquo;purple partnership&rsquo; helping Australians with epilepsy in March',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2014-03-10','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:24:34','2016-10-03 00:56:25','2016-10-03 11:26:11'),(161,602,2,0,17,'MedicAlert Foundation &lsquo;purple partnership&rsquo; helping Australians with epilepsy in March',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-foundation-andlsquopurple-partnershipandrsquo-helping-australians-with-epilepsy-in-march',0,'The month-long partnership with Epilepsy Australia that will see five dollars from every purple coloured MedicAlert medical ID sold during March donated to the organisation dedicated to helping ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>The month-long partnership with Epilepsy Australia that will see five dollars from every purple coloured MedicAlert medical ID sold during March donated to the organisation dedicated to helping Australians living with epilepsy, has started very positively.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, says it is pleasing to be able to support a fellow not-for-profit organisation and help to raise funds for Epilepsy Australia so it can continue to provide education, information and assistance to Australians living with epilepsy.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This is a way that lets our members play a role in helping to raise funds for a worthy cause by buying one of our new purple coloured medical IDs during the month of March,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;More than 400,000 Australians are believed to have epilepsy, and rather than focus our support just on the 26<sup>th</sup> March for Purple Day, we wanted to dedicate the entire month to encouraging people to wear a purple medical ID and help spread the word about epilepsy,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s also a way to add support to our many members who live with epilepsy and for them, knowing that should they have a sudden seizure then our distinctive emblem can speak for them &ndash; with their critical health information engraved and clearly visible on the back of their easily recognisable emblem,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner says the response from members so far this month has been extremely positive.</p>\r\n<p>As part of its service to members, MedicAlert Foundation provides a 24/7 hotline where emergency service personnel and healthcare professionals can access important additional medical and other details quickly and efficiently in a time of need.</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, Australia Medic Alert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service with close to 300,000 members joining since 1971.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation &lsquo;purple partnership&rsquo; helping Australians with epilepsy in March',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2014-03-10','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:24:34','2016-10-10 06:42:59',NULL),(162,603,2,0,17,'&#039;What Matters To You&#039; Competition Winners',NULL,NULL,'what-matters-to-you-competition-winners',0,'Thank you to everyone who entered our &#039;What Matters To You&#039; competition! ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Thank you to everyone who entered our &#039;What Matters To You&#039; competition! We had just over 600 entries and it was very difficult trying to decide on only 6 winners. The winners are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nerida Robinson, NSW</li>\r\n<li>Sharryn Shaw, VIC</li>\r\n<li>Michael Welden, SA</li>\r\n<li>Jeremy Ko, NSW</li>\r\n<li>Lola Mudie, QLD</li>\r\n<li>Graham Connolly, WA</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>CONGRATULATIONS to our winners! Your gift certificates will be posted out to you this week.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'&#039;What Matters To You&#039; Competition Winners',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-11-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:26:54','2016-10-10 05:16:10',NULL),(163,604,2,0,17,'Message to members',NULL,NULL,'message-to-members',0,'Some of you may have noted media reports following the recent findings of a Coronial enquiry into the sudden and tragic death of a female MedicAlert Foundation member in a Queensland hospital in 2010','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Some of you may have noted media reports following the recent findings of a Coronial enquiry into the sudden and tragic death of a female MedicAlert&reg; Foundation member in a Queensland hospital in 2010.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation provided information to assist with the Coronial enquiry and remains committed to supporting Queensland Health in every way possible to ensure the best protection for our Queensland members and the total 160,000 current members across the nation.</p>\r\n<p>Two critical points of fact are clear in this case &ndash; firstly, both sides of the emblem on the bracelet show significant signs of wear despite being made of durable stainless steel. Secondly, the responding healthcare professionals in the hospital failed to immediately look for and recognise the emblem and that created a delay in noting the personal medical details that are inscribed on the reverse of the emblem.</p>\r\n<p>One important thing that this tragedy highlights is the responsibility of all MedicAlert Foundation members to regularly inspect their emblems to ensure they remain functional and readable and to always update their personal medical and contact information as a priority.</p>\r\n<p>The Coroner has flagged the need for all emergency ID&rsquo;s to place function over fashion, and I believe this remains the top-of-mind consideration for MedicAlert Foundation. To ensure they are worn as part of a daily routine, our range of emblems strike a balance between being functional and appropriate for a modern lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p>Since the Foundation was first established in Australia in 1971, we have kept the internationally-recognised logo unchanged, and today we remain the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit, member-based organisation that provides a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service. The Rod of Aesclepius (international symbol for medicine) and the words &lsquo;Medic&rsquo; and &lsquo;Alert&rsquo; form the very distinctive and self-explanatory logo.</p>\r\n<p>A lack of formalised standards has given rise to a number of me-too products being introduced to the marketplace in recent years and some offer questionable value and useability. In response, in 2011 the Foundation developed an <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/Code-of-Conduct&quot;>International Code of Conduct</a> relating to medical identification emblems and continues to encourage every other medical identification provider to follow the voluntary Code.</p>\r\n<p>In our 42 years in Australia the Foundation&lsquo;s product range has evolved to meet changing needs. Many members have told us that they change the bracelet or necklace provided with their distinctive emblem so it is something both functional and fashionable. Without this flexibility, many say they would not wear the emblem at all.</p>\r\n<p>Our aim is to ensure that all emergency service and healthcare professionals are aware of the MedicAlert emblem and why it is critical they always look for it and act upon the information engraved, because that is what matters most to our members.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sandra Turner</strong><br />Chief Executive Officer<br />Australia Medic Alert Foundation</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Message to members',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-10-31','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:29:54','2016-10-03 01:01:52','2016-10-03 11:31:38'),(164,604,2,0,17,'Message to members',NULL,NULL,'message-to-members',0,'Some of you may have noted media reports following the recent findings of a Coronial enquiry into the sudden and tragic death of a female MedicAlert Foundation member in a Queensland hospital in 2010','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Some of you may have noted media reports following the recent findings of a Coronial enquiry into the sudden and tragic death of a female MedicAlert&reg; Foundation member in a Queensland hospital in 2010.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation provided information to assist with the Coronial enquiry and remains committed to supporting Queensland Health in every way possible to ensure the best protection for our Queensland members and the total 160,000 current members across the nation.</p>\r\n<p>Two critical points of fact are clear in this case &ndash; firstly, both sides of the emblem on the bracelet show significant signs of wear despite being made of durable stainless steel. Secondly, the responding healthcare professionals in the hospital failed to immediately look for and recognise the emblem and that created a delay in noting the personal medical details that are inscribed on the reverse of the emblem.</p>\r\n<p>One important thing that this tragedy highlights is the responsibility of all MedicAlert Foundation members to regularly inspect their emblems to ensure they remain functional and readable and to always update their personal medical and contact information as a priority.</p>\r\n<p>The Coroner has flagged the need for all emergency ID&rsquo;s to place function over fashion, and I believe this remains the top-of-mind consideration for MedicAlert Foundation. To ensure they are worn as part of a daily routine, our range of emblems strike a balance between being functional and appropriate for a modern lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p>Since the Foundation was first established in Australia in 1971, we have kept the internationally-recognised logo unchanged, and today we remain the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit, member-based organisation that provides a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service. The Rod of Aesclepius (international symbol for medicine) and the words &lsquo;Medic&rsquo; and &lsquo;Alert&rsquo; form the very distinctive and self-explanatory logo.</p>\r\n<p>A lack of formalised standards has given rise to a number of me-too products being introduced to the marketplace in recent years and some offer questionable value and useability. In response, in 2011 the Foundation developed an <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/Code-of-Conduct&quot;>International Code of Conduct</a> relating to medical identification emblems and continues to encourage every other medical identification provider to follow the voluntary Code.</p>\r\n<p>In our 42 years in Australia the Foundation&lsquo;s product range has evolved to meet changing needs. Many members have told us that they change the bracelet or necklace provided with their distinctive emblem so it is something both functional and fashionable. Without this flexibility, many say they would not wear the emblem at all.</p>\r\n<p>Our aim is to ensure that all emergency service and healthcare professionals are aware of the MedicAlert emblem and why it is critical they always look for it and act upon the information engraved, because that is what matters most to our members.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sandra Turner</strong><br />Chief Executive Officer<br />Australia Medic Alert Foundation</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Message to members',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-10-31','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:29:54','2016-10-10 05:23:23',NULL),(165,605,2,0,17,'Wear What Matters during Awareness Week, says MedicAlert Foundation',NULL,NULL,'wear-what-matters-during-awareness-week-says-medicalert-foundation',0,'On October 20th Australia Medic Alert Foundation will launch its week-long &lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo; Awareness Campaign to highlight how wearing its distinctive emblem can help individuals in times of need.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>On October 20<sup>th</sup> Australia Medic Alert Foundation will launch its week-long <em>&lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo;</em> Awareness Campaign to highlight how wearing its distinctive emblem can help individuals in times of need.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, says the <em>&lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo;</em> campaign promotes the benefits of wearing a genuine MedicAlert medical ID on the neck or wrist to provide critical medical and other information when it is needed most.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Whilst our campaign has an element of fun about it, our underlying message to all Australians living with a medical condition and / or special needs is that they can be confident knowing their important medical information can be communicated quickly in a medical or other emergency if they are wearing a genuine MedicAlert emblem,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Ask &ldquo;what matters most?&rdquo; to someone you know and chances are that you&rsquo;ll get a different answer every time &ndash; and for someone with a serious health issue, often what matters most is being able to live a safe and healthy life and MedicAlert membership can certainly help to make that happen.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The <em>Wear What Matters</em> campaign reminds everyone that should they come across someone having a seizure, is incoherent or unconscious and isn&rsquo;t able to say what is wrong with them, to check around the neck and wrist points for the easily recognisable MedicAlert logo for potentially life-saving medical information.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner said that too often people join MedicAlert Foundation after they or a loved one have survived a near-miss event and encouraged people to become more proactive with their health management and not leave it until such a close-call.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We also want to remind our existing members that have stopped wearing their emblem for some reason to put it back on &ndash; and better still to not to take it off at all,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This is also a timely reminder for members to check emblems for wear and confirm and update their details held on file to ensure they are provided with the best possible assistance when it is most needed,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Having a medical condition doesn&rsquo;t need to hold anyone back from living life to the fullest and when it comes to wearing what matters, the reality is that we &ndash; MedicAlert Foundation &ndash; are what matters when it comes to being healthy and staying safe.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The <em>Wear What Matters</em> Awareness Week will run from the 20<sup>th</sup> - 26<sup>th</sup> of October, with a dedicated website that provides more information about the Week, member testimonials and a fun interactive game to play.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;<em>Wear What Matters</em> has a prominent online component, and people can learn first-hand from some of our members who owe their lives to their MedicAlert emblem and who wear one of our emblems as part of their own personal risk-management strategy,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our members want to know that the right help is available when it is needed most and it&rsquo;s very important to them to have their vital information relayed quickly in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This Week is also the perfect opportunity to thank the many emergency service workers and healthcare professionals that regularly look for our emblem when they treat one of our members both in the emergency situation and along the healthcare journey.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>For more information about <em>Wear What Matters</em>, go to the website at <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/wear-what-matters&quot;>www.medicalert.org.au/wear-what-matters</a></p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Wear What Matters during Awareness Week, says MedicAlert Foundation',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-10-21','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:33:01','2016-10-03 01:09:23','2016-10-03 11:39:09'),(166,605,2,0,17,'Wear What Matters during Awareness Week, says MedicAlert Foundation',NULL,NULL,'wear-what-matters-during-awareness-week-says-medicalert-foundation',0,'On October 20th Australia Medic Alert Foundation will launch its week-long &lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo; Awareness Campaign to highlight how wearing its distinctive emblem can help individuals in times of need.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>On October 20<sup>th</sup> Australia Medic Alert Foundation will launch its week-long <em>&lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo;</em> Awareness Campaign to highlight how wearing its distinctive emblem can help individuals in times of need.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, says the <em>&lsquo;Wear What Matters&rsquo;</em> campaign promotes the benefits of wearing a genuine MedicAlert medical ID on the neck or wrist to provide critical medical a