t Foundation &ndash; are what matters when it comes to being healthy and staying safe.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The <em>Wear What Matters</em> Awareness Week will run from the 20<sup>th</sup> - 26<sup>th</sup> of October, with a dedicated website that provides more information about the Week, member testimonials and a fun interactive game to play.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;<em>Wear What Matters</em> has a prominent online component, and people can learn first-hand from some of our members who owe their lives to their MedicAlert emblem and who wear one of our emblems as part of their own personal risk-management strategy,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our members want to know that the right help is available when it is needed most and it&rsquo;s very important to them to have their vital information relayed quickly in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This Week is also the perfect opportunity to thank the many emergency service workers and healthcare professionals that regularly look for our emblem when they treat one of our members both in the emergency situation and along the healthcare journey.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>For more information about <em>Wear What Matters</em>, go to the website at <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/wear-what-matters&quot;>www.medicalert.org.au/wear-what-matters</a></p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Wear What Matters during Awareness Week, says MedicAlert Foundation',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-10-21','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:33:01','2016-10-10 05:22:28',NULL),(167,606,2,0,17,'MedicAlert Foundation urges people with haemophilia to better protect themselves',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-foundation-urges-people-with-haemophilia-to-better-protect-themselves',0,'With April 17 marking World Haemophilia Day, MedicAlert Foundation has urged people with haemophilia and other inherited bleeding disorders to make non-medical precautions a compulsory part of their ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p><strong>With April 17 marking World Haemophilia Day, MedicAlert Foundation has urged people with haemophilia and other inherited bleeding disorders to make non-medical precautions a compulsory part of their personal risk-management strategy. More than 240,000 people globally have been diagnosed with haemophilia, including approximately 2,600 Australians, with varied degrees of severity.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Haemophilia, von Willebrand&rsquo;s and other inherited clotting factor deficiencies are lifelong bleeding disorders that prevent blood from clotting properly, meaning that people with bleeding disorders could face a higher level of risk just by going about their daily lives.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner said that people with bleeding disorders want to strike a balance between managing their medical risks and living a full life.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Some choose to become MedicAlert Foundation members knowing that the important medical information regarding their condition is available in an emergency if they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People with haemophilia don&rsquo;t bleed any faster than normal, but they can bleed for longer and in a trauma situation, knowing someone has haemophilia or any other bleeding disorder can be critical to their care,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Whether someone is at home, in the community or even travelling overseas, their possibly life-saving medical information is always with our members on the back of the distinctive MedicAlert emblem which is either worn around the neck or wrist.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>After being diagnosed with von Willebrand disorder after the birth of her son, Fiona Smith chose to become a MedicAlert Foundation member for additional piece of mind. The28-year old mother from Western Australian is using World Haemophilia Day to urge others to also make the same decision.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Whether I am suddenly involved in a car crash or injure myself in some other way, it is important that a paramedic, doctor, nurse or some other health professional that comes to my aid is aware of my condition &ndash; especially if I am not conscious and unable to talk for myself,&rdquo; Mrs Smith said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I know of incidents where people with von Willebrand disorder have tragically died because emergency crews didn&rsquo;t know about their condition until it was too late, and when I was recently rushed to hospital my Medic Alert membership let the ambulance crew know immediately and they could administer the treatment I needed,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;You never know what life will throw at you, and becoming a MedicAlert member could mean that one day it saves my life during a situation where I have no control.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, the Australia MedicAlert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service.</p>\r\n<p>To find out more about the MedicAlert Foundation and how to become a member, visit <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/&quot;>http://www.medicalert.org.au/</a></p>\r\n<p>For more information about haemophilia, go to <a href=&quot;http://www.haemophilia.org.au/&quot;>http://www.haemophilia.org.au/</a></p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation urges people with haemophilia to better protect themselves',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-04-17','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:40:07','2016-10-03 01:11:33','2016-10-03 11:41:19'),(168,606,2,0,17,'MedicAlert Foundation urges people with haemophilia to better protect themselves',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-foundation-urges-people-with-haemophilia-to-better-protect-themselves',0,'With April 17 marking World Haemophilia Day, MedicAlert Foundation has urged people with haemophilia and other inherited bleeding disorders to make non-medical precautions a compulsory part of their ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>With April 17 marking World Haemophilia Day, MedicAlert Foundation has urged people with haemophilia and other inherited bleeding disorders to make non-medical precautions a compulsory part of their personal risk-management strategy. More than 240,000 people globally have been diagnosed with haemophilia, including approximately 2,600 Australians, with varied degrees of severity.</p>\r\n<p>Haemophilia, von Willebrand&rsquo;s and other inherited clotting factor deficiencies are lifelong bleeding disorders that prevent blood from clotting properly, meaning that people with bleeding disorders could face a higher level of risk just by going about their daily lives.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner said that people with bleeding disorders want to strike a balance between managing their medical risks and living a full life.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Some choose to become MedicAlert Foundation members knowing that the important medical information regarding their condition is available in an emergency if they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People with haemophilia don&rsquo;t bleed any faster than normal, but they can bleed for longer and in a trauma situation, knowing someone has haemophilia or any other bleeding disorder can be critical to their care,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Whether someone is at home, in the community or even travelling overseas, their possibly life-saving medical information is always with our members on the back of the distinctive MedicAlert emblem which is either worn around the neck or wrist.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>After being diagnosed with von Willebrand disorder after the birth of her son, Fiona Smith chose to become a MedicAlert Foundation member for additional piece of mind. The28-year old mother from Western Australian is using World Haemophilia Day to urge others to also make the same decision.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Whether I am suddenly involved in a car crash or injure myself in some other way, it is important that a paramedic, doctor, nurse or some other health professional that comes to my aid is aware of my condition &ndash; especially if I am not conscious and unable to talk for myself,&rdquo; Mrs Smith said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I know of incidents where people with von Willebrand disorder have tragically died because emergency crews didn&rsquo;t know about their condition until it was too late, and when I was recently rushed to hospital my Medic Alert membership let the ambulance crew know immediately and they could administer the treatment I needed,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;You never know what life will throw at you, and becoming a MedicAlert member could mean that one day it saves my life during a situation where I have no control.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, the Australia MedicAlert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service.</p>\r\n<p>To find out more about the MedicAlert Foundation and how to become a member, visit <a href=&quot;http://www.medicalert.org.au/&quot;>www.medicalert.org.au</a></p>\r\n<p>For more information about haemophilia, go to <a href=&quot;http://www.haemophilia.org.au/&quot;>www.haemophilia.org.au</a></p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation urges people with haemophilia to better protect themselves',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-04-17','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:40:07','2016-10-10 05:24:08',NULL),(169,607,2,0,17,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation supporting people with epilepsy',NULL,NULL,'australia-medic-alert-foundation-supporting-people-with-epilepsy',0,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation has thrown its support behind National Epilepsy Awareness Month and today&rsquo;s worldwide Purple Day event designed to raise awareness of epilepsy and reminds Australians ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p><strong>Australia Medic Alert Foundation has thrown its support behind National Epilepsy Awareness Month and today&rsquo;s worldwide Purple Day event designed to raise awareness of epilepsy and reminds Australians of the need to look for the Foundation&rsquo;s distinctive emblem if they encounter someone in difficulty.</strong></p>\r\n<p>According to the World Health Organisation, epilepsy is the world&#039;s most common serious brain disorder and it impacts the lives of 400,000 Australians.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert&trade; Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, said many Australians living with epilepsy are Foundation members and they always wear the distinctive MedicAlert emblem on a necklace or wrist band to advise of their condition should a seizure occur.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The engraved emblem provides important medical information to assist with immediate care and can also help with identification of the individual, so it is important to look for it,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our members living with epilepsy want to live confident lives and with the peace of mind that comes with knowing the emblem can &lsquo;speak for them&rsquo; if they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Epilepsy is a sometimes unpredictable condition and seizures come in many different forms. There are often no early warning signs and any one of us might come across someone in need of help as we go about our daily lives.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner said that it&rsquo;s important to stay calm if with someone having a seizure and to call for emergency assistance if required.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A seizure can be very distressing for the person, so protect them from injury wherever possible, monitor their breathing and gently reassure them until help arrives. If the person is wearing a MedicAlert emblem, pass that engraved information on to the ambulance service,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, the Australia Medic Alert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation supporting people with epilepsy',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-03-26','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:42:42','2016-10-03 01:13:54','2016-10-03 11:43:40'),(170,607,2,0,17,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation supporting people with epilepsy',NULL,NULL,'australia-medic-alert-foundation-supporting-people-with-epilepsy',0,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation has thrown its support behind National Epilepsy Awareness Month and today&rsquo;s worldwide Purple Day event designed to raise awareness of epilepsy and reminds Australians ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation has thrown its support behind National Epilepsy Awareness Month and today&rsquo;s worldwide Purple Day event designed to raise awareness of epilepsy and reminds Australians of the need to look for the Foundation&rsquo;s distinctive emblem if they encounter someone in difficulty.</p>\r\n<p>According to the World Health Organisation, epilepsy is the world&#039;s most common serious brain disorder and it impacts the lives of 400,000 Australians.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert&trade; Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, said many Australians living with epilepsy are Foundation members and they always wear the distinctive MedicAlert emblem on a necklace or wrist band to advise of their condition should a seizure occur.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The engraved emblem provides important medical information to assist with immediate care and can also help with identification of the individual, so it is important to look for it,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Our members living with epilepsy want to live confident lives and with the peace of mind that comes with knowing the emblem can &lsquo;speak for them&rsquo; if they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Epilepsy is a sometimes unpredictable condition and seizures come in many different forms. There are often no early warning signs and any one of us might come across someone in need of help as we go about our daily lives.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner said that it&rsquo;s important to stay calm if with someone having a seizure and to call for emergency assistance if required.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;A seizure can be very distressing for the person, so protect them from injury wherever possible, monitor their breathing and gently reassure them until help arrives. If the person is wearing a MedicAlert emblem, pass that engraved information on to the ambulance service,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, the Australia Medic Alert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation supporting people with epilepsy',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-03-26','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:42:42','2016-10-10 06:42:19',NULL),(171,608,2,0,17,'MedicAlert Foundation launches major national awareness program',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-foundation-launches-major-national-awareness-program',0,'Australia Medic Alert Foundation has launched a major national awareness campaign designed to remind Australians that taking a few seconds to check for its distinctive emblem could save a life when ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation has launched a major national awareness campaign designed to remind Australians that taking a few seconds to check for its distinctive emblem could save a life when they encounter someone in difficulty.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation CEO, Sandra Turner, said the national campaign combines a mix of television advertising, online activity and use of social media such as Facebook and YouTube to help reinforce the need to look for the distinct MedicAlert emblem in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Default&quot;>&ldquo;Whether it is at home, in the community or even overseas, any one of us may be first at a scene where someone may be having a seizure, may have passed out or for some reason isn&rsquo;t able to tell you what is wrong with them or provide any medical history before emergency services arrive,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Default&quot;>&ldquo;It is important to look for the internationally recognised symbol of the MedicAlert Foundation which is worn on the wrist or around the neck, because it contains information that could be life-saving. Importantly, the emblem does not have to be removed from the person in the emergency situation in order to read the information engraved on the back of the emblem.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner said that as thousands of children are now back to school, it&rsquo;s a timely reminder that allergies, diabetes and other medical conditions are non-selective and children and adults alike are vulnerable, especially if they are away from friends and family who understand their medical and other needs.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Default&quot;>&ldquo;The MedicAlert emblem offers peace of mind to all Australians with a medical condition, allergy or special needs. Our members have the freedom to live their lives to the fullest knowing their important medical information is available in an emergency if they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Default&quot;>&ldquo;There is no second chance when seconds count, and taking the time to check for a MedicAlert emblem could make the difference between someone surviving an emergency or not,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We believe the mediums we have chosen for our awareness campaign offer an opportunity to educate people about what to look for in an emergency and we hope our community service announcement and YouTube video sticks in peoples&rsquo; minds and serves as a prompt,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Default&quot;>As part of the service, MedicAlert Foundation provides a 24/7 hotline for healthcare and emergency service workers to call if they need additional member information.</p>\r\n<p>For over 40 years, the Australia Medic Alert Foundation has been the nation&rsquo;s only not-for-profit organisation providing a 24/7 personal medical emergency information and identification service.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation launches major national awareness program',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2013-02-05','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:45:31','2016-10-10 05:25:01',NULL),(172,609,2,0,17,'Carers need care too',NULL,NULL,'carers-need-care-too',0,'In Australia today, over 2.9 million people are providing help and health support to a family member or friend [1]. ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>In Australia today, over 2.9 million people are providing help and health support to a family member or friend<sup>1</sup>. While these people spend their time thinking about the well being of another it&rsquo;s vital that they consider their own health too. MedicAlert Foundation provides a service that can help protect them and those they care for&hellip;</p>\r\n<p>Imagine being responsible for the care of someone who couldn&rsquo;t look after themselves either as a result of illness, accident or old age. Being the person they rely on 24 hours a day, every day of the year. That&rsquo;s the reality for many Australians who provide unpaid support to a family member, friend or neighbour in need of assistance.</p>\r\n<p>Whether the role of being a carer is taken on by necessity or choice, all carers are special people who are to be admired for their selfless dedication to another&rsquo;s wellbeing.</p>\r\n<p>The very nature of being a carer demands that someone else&rsquo;s needs are often put first and the job can be both physically and emotionally draining. Although often overlooked, carers need to consider their health and support too.</p>\r\n<p>Carers need to eat well and drink plenty of water. Exercise and getting enough sleep are also important. Taking time out should always be a priority &ndash; getting together with friends regularly, joining a social group or getting away for a short holiday every now and then are all good ideas. It&rsquo;s also important to remember that there are support organisations throughout Australia whose sole aim is to make life easier for those whose job it is to care for another.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation also assists carers. It&rsquo;s interesting to note that carers are 40 per cent more likely than the rest of the population to suffer from a chronic health condition<sup>1</sup>. For those carers afflicted with such a condition, a MedicAlert membership is a great idea.</p>\r\n<p>But MedicAlert Foundation also provides peace of mind for those who are fortunate enough to be in good health. Members can wear an emblem that not only specifies any individual health conditions but their information can also communicate the fact that they are responsible for another&rsquo;s well being too. Should their own personal medical emergency arise, carers can rest assured that their MedicAlert emblem will bring to the attention of healthcare responders that there&rsquo;s someone dear to them requiring assistance.</p>\r\n<p>Looking after yourself means you will be more effective in looking after others. So, if you&rsquo;re a carer, please take the time to consider what you can do for yourself and those you care about, and remember, we&rsquo;re <em>always there for you</em>.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=&quot;padding-left: 5px;&quot;>[1] Healey, J (ed.) 2012,<em> Carers: Ageing and Disability, </em>vol. 342, The Spiney Press.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Carers need care too',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-08-28','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:47:21','2016-10-03 01:20:03','2016-10-03 11:49:49'),(173,609,2,0,17,'Carers need care too',NULL,NULL,'carers-need-care-too',0,'In Australia today, over 2.9 million people are providing help and health support to a family member or friend [1]. ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>In Australia today, over 2.9 million people are providing help and health support to a family member or friend<sup>1</sup>. While these people spend their time thinking about the well being of another it&rsquo;s vital that they consider their own health too. MedicAlert Foundation provides a service that can help protect them and those they care for&hellip;</p>\r\n<p>Imagine being responsible for the care of someone who couldn&rsquo;t look after themselves either as a result of illness, accident or old age. Being the person they rely on 24 hours a day, every day of the year. That&rsquo;s the reality for many Australians who provide unpaid support to a family member, friend or neighbour in need of assistance.</p>\r\n<p>Whether the role of being a carer is taken on by necessity or choice, all carers are special people who are to be admired for their selfless dedication to another&rsquo;s wellbeing.</p>\r\n<p>The very nature of being a carer demands that someone else&rsquo;s needs are often put first and the job can be both physically and emotionally draining. Although often overlooked, carers need to consider their health and support too.</p>\r\n<p>Carers need to eat well and drink plenty of water. Exercise and getting enough sleep are also important. Taking time out should always be a priority &ndash; getting together with friends regularly, joining a social group or getting away for a short holiday every now and then are all good ideas. It&rsquo;s also important to remember that there are support organisations throughout Australia whose sole aim is to make life easier for those whose job it is to care for another.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation also assists carers. It&rsquo;s interesting to note that carers are 40 per cent more likely than the rest of the population to suffer from a chronic health condition<sup>1</sup>. For those carers afflicted with such a condition, a MedicAlert membership is a great idea.</p>\r\n<p>But MedicAlert Foundation also provides peace of mind for those who are fortunate enough to be in good health. Members can wear an emblem that not only specifies any individual health conditions but their information can also communicate the fact that they are responsible for another&rsquo;s well being too. Should their own personal medical emergency arise, carers can rest assured that their MedicAlert emblem will bring to the attention of healthcare responders that there&rsquo;s someone dear to them requiring assistance.</p>\r\n<p>Looking after yourself means you will be more effective in looking after others. So, if you&rsquo;re a carer, please take the time to consider what you can do for yourself and those you care about, and remember, we&rsquo;re <em>always there for you</em>.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=&quot;padding-left: 5px;&quot;>[1] Healey, J (ed.) 2012,<em> Carers: Ageing and Disability, </em>vol. 342, The Spiney Press.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Carers need care too',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2012-08-28','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:47:21','2016-10-10 05:19:03',NULL),(174,610,2,0,17,'Managing life with diabetes',NULL,NULL,'managing-life-with-diabetes',0,'Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our ','<p>Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our nation by raising awareness of the disease, its risk factors and how to appropriately manage it.</p>\r\n<p>CEO of Australia Medic Alert Foundation, Sandra Turner, says her team sees new members joining everyday and diabetes and allergy constitute the two most frequent medical condition groups seen.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Not a day goes by where we don&rsquo;t see at least two to three new members joining with diabetes stated as a current medical condition,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>For those affected by the disease it&rsquo;s important that the right resources and care are available. A vital part of managing diabetes is to ensure that those living with the disease can alert those around them to their condition should an emergency arise.</p>\r\n<p>The not for profit Foundation provides members with the internationally recognised MedicAlert&reg; emblem that is used to alert emergency and healthcare professionals to a person&rsquo;s immediate medical needs in times of emergency or when they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner says the custom engraved MedicAlert medical ID is a simple and effective way to provide additional support to people living with diabetes, especially if their disease is poorly controlled.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Anyone living with diabetes and especially those with unstable disease need to be able to alert others to their condition quickly and effectively - it could save their life,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation member, Greg Sutton, of Onkaparinga Hills in South Australia, feels more confident that he will get the right care in times of need because he wears his emblem all the time.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert is part of my well-being plan,&rdquo; said Greg.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While my diabetes is quite stable, my MedicAlert emblem gives me great peace of mind knowing that it could save my life if I was in an accident,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>1.7 million Australians have diabetes and up to half of type 2 diabetes cases remain undiagnosed[1]. The disease is ranked sixth in the leading causes of death in Australians according to Diabetes Australia and there is currently no cure[1].</p>\r\n<p>For more information on diabetes please visit <a href=&quot;http://www.diabetesaustralia.com.au.&quot;>www.diabetesaustralia.com.au.</a></p>\r\n<p>[1] AusDiab, 2005 The Australian Diabetes Obesity and Lifestyle Study. 2005 NSW Health, AusDiab.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Managing life with diabetes',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-09','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:50:40','2016-10-03 01:24:32','2016-10-03 11:54:19'),(175,610,2,0,17,'Managing life with diabetes',NULL,NULL,'managing-life-with-diabetes',0,'Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our ','<p>Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our nation by raising awareness of the disease, its risk factors and how to appropriately manage it.</p>\r\n<p>CEO of Australia Medic Alert Foundation, Sandra Turner, says her team sees new members joining everyday and diabetes and allergy constitute the two most frequent medical condition groups seen.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Not a day goes by where we don&rsquo;t see at least two to three new members joining with diabetes stated as a current medical condition,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>For those affected by the disease it&rsquo;s important that the right resources and care are available. A vital part of managing diabetes is to ensure that those living with the disease can alert those around them to their condition should an emergency arise.</p>\r\n<p>The not for profit Foundation provides members with the internationally recognised MedicAlert&reg; emblem that is used to alert emergency and healthcare professionals to a person&rsquo;s immediate medical needs in times of emergency or when they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner says the custom engraved MedicAlert medical ID is a simple and effective way to provide additional support to people living with diabetes, especially if their disease is poorly controlled.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Anyone living with diabetes and especially those with unstable disease need to be able to alert others to their condition quickly and effectively - it could save their life,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert Foundation member, Greg Sutton, of Onkaparinga Hills in South Australia, feels more confident that he will get the right care in times of need because he wears his emblem all the time.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert is part of my well-being plan,&rdquo; said Greg.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;While my diabetes is quite stable, my MedicAlert emblem gives me great peace of mind knowing that it could save my life if I was in an accident,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>1.7 million Australians have diabetes and up to half of type 2 diabetes cases remain undiagnosed[1]. The disease is ranked sixth in the leading causes of death in Australians according to Diabetes Australia and there is currently no cure[1].</p>\r\n<p>For more information on diabetes please visit <a href=&quot;http://www.diabetesaustralia.com.au&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>www.diabetesaustralia.com.au</a></p>\r\n<p>[1] AusDiab, 2005 The Australian Diabetes Obesity and Lifestyle Study. 2005 NSW Health, AusDiab.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Managing life with diabetes',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-07-09','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 11:50:40','2016-10-03 01:24:38','2016-10-03 11:54:25'),(176,610,2,0,17,'Managing life with diabetes',NULL,NULL,'managing-life-with-diabetes',0,'Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our ','<p>Diabetes is one of the most significant health issues faced by Australians in recent decades. Diabetes Awareness week, 8 - 14 July, is dedicated to limiting the stronghold the disease has on our nation by raising awareness of the disease, its risk factors and how to appropriately manage it.</p>\r\n<p>CEO of Australia Medic Alert Foundation, Sandra Turner, says her team sees new members joining everyday and diabetes and allergy constitute the two most frequent medical condition groups seen.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Not a day goes by where we don&rsquo;t see at least two to three new members joining with diabetes stated as a current medical condition,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>For those affected by the disease it&rsquo;s important that the right resources and care are available. A vital part of managing diabetes is to ensure that those living with the disease can alert those around them to their condition should an emergency arise.</p>\r\n<p>The not for profit Foundation provides members with the internationally recognised MedicAlert&reg; emblem that is used to alert emergency and healthcare professionals to a person&rsquo;s immediate medical needs in times of emergency or when they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves.</p>\r\n<p>Ms Turner says the custom engraved MedicAlert medical ID is a simple and effective way to provide additional support to people living with diabetes, especially if their disease is poorly controlled.</p>\r\n<p>&ldqu