their health and to encourage them to be more aware of how to manage health-related issues.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>Australian Bureau of Statistics studies show that men are more likely than women to suffer from conditions such as skin and lung cancers and ischaemic heart disease.<a title=&quot;&quot; href=&quot;file:///C:/Users/kmoffatt/AppData/Local/Microsoft/Windows/Temporary%20Internet%20Files/Content.Outlook/LVAF0GY4/Men%27s%20Health%20Week%20June%202012.docx#_ftn1&quot;>[1]</a></p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>MedicAlert Foundation&reg; has close to 70,000 male members in Australia who wear the genuine MedicAlert emblem around their neck or on their wrist every day to help protect them in times of medical emergency - so they know what works.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>According to the Foundation&rsquo;s Chief Executive Officer, Sandra Turner, encouraging males to wear an emblem to advise of specific medical conditions, medications and special needs is sometimes a challenge as some men are not keen to wear any type of emblem or jewellery, and it can be life-saving in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>&ldquo;We know that ambulance and emergency service personnel will look around the neck and on the wrist for medical identification, and having been in Australia for 41 years, the MedicAlert emblem is well-recognised and trusted to provide important information immediately,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>&ldquo;For someone who can&rsquo;t speak for themselves in an emergency situation, what&rsquo;s engraved on the back of the MedicAlert emblem can help save their life,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>For Alan Mingo of Five Dock, NSW, it&rsquo;s not a question of whether to wear an emblem, it&rsquo;s a decision of which one depending on his activity. Alan has both a bracelet and a pendant to choose from.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>Although Alan is retired, he still spends a lot of time away from home and never goes anywhere without his MedicAlert emblem. He carries his MedicAlert card in his wallet and has a spare on his car dashboard.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>Alan has a medical condition that requires special medication and in an emergency, he needs to know those caring for him will understand the implications if he is sick or injured, and especially if he isn&rsquo;t able to tell them himself.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t go anywhere without it, even when I travel overseas,&rdquo; said Alan.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a simple way to protect me and the emblem has helped me a couple of times in recent years,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>Alan hopes that his experiences may encourage other men to also consider wearing a MedicAlert emblem if they have any significant medical conditions that may require urgent attention in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d rather people be pre-warned and pre-armed. If you don&rsquo;t do everything you can to protect yourself in advance, it may be too late,&rdquo; said Alan.</p>\r\n<div><br clear=&quot;all&quot; /><hr align=&quot;left&quot; size=&quot;1&quot; width=&quot;33%&quot; />\r\n<div>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;><a title=&quot;&quot; href=&quot;file:///C:/Users/kmoffatt/AppData/Local/Microsoft/Windows/Temporary%20Internet%20Files/Content.Outlook/LVAF0GY4/Men%27s%20Health%20Week%20June%202012.docx#_ftnref1&quot;>[1]</a> Australian Bureau of Statistics</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;Body&quot;><a href=&quot;http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/BBC4B00DFF0E942ACA2579C6000F6B15?opendocument&quot;>http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/BBC4B00DFF0E942ACA2579C6000F6B15?opendocument</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert Foundation proudly supporting Men&#039;s Health Week (11-17 June)',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012-06-11','2020-12-31',