,NULL,'2011-12-19','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:18:17','2016-10-10 05:17:09',NULL),(195,625,2,0,17,'Australian medical icon fit at 40',NULL,NULL,'australian-medical-icon-fit-at-40',0,'From its simple beginnings as a stainless steel bracelet, the widely recognised MedicAlert emblem provides a proven &lsquo;break-glass&rsquo; system protecting many thousands of Australians over the past 40 year','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<h4>From its simple beginnings as a stainless steel bracelet, the widely recognised MedicAlert<sup>&reg;</sup> emblem provides a proven &lsquo;break-glass&rsquo; system protecting many thousands of Australians over the past 40 years.</h4>\r\n<p>The MedicAlert emblem, worn on the wrist or neck, relays vital information to emergency responders about the wearer&rsquo;s medical conditions, allergies and medications, so they receive faster, safer treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Californian physician and surgeon, Dr Marion Collins, designed the first MedicAlert bracelet in 1956 after his 14-year-old daughter almost died due to a severe allergy to a tetanus antitoxin skin test.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation, chief executive officer, Ms Sandra Turner, says Rotary and the St John Council realised the enduring value of this simple idea when they supported the introduction of the non-profit Foundation into Australia in 1971.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert emblem allows people to play an active part in their healthcare by ensuring their critical medical and personal details are communicated to emergency service and healthcare professionals quickly, especially when they can&rsquo;t speak for themselves,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>Executive Director of Patient Services at SA Ambulance Service, Keith Driscoll, says the emblem can and does help save lives.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Anyone living with a life-threatening medical condition should consider wearing the easily-recognised MedicAlert emblem,&rdquo; said Mr Driscoll.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Having important medical information available immediately helps ambulance officers to start the right treatment earlier and they are trained to check the neck and wrist for medical identification,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>There is only one genuine MedicAlert emblem, engraved with the words &lsquo;Medic&rsquo; and &lsquo;Alert&rsquo; on each side of the Rod of Asclepius, the international symbol of medicine.</p>\r\n<p>The service provided to members includes a professionally staffed 24/7 emergency hotline enabling emergency and healthcare personnel to quickly access vital member information.</p>\r\n<p>The Foundation conducts ongoing education campaigns for emergency service providers and healthcare professionals to ensure they routinely check for medical identification and understand how it supports life-saving treatment when seconds can make all the difference.</p>\r\n<p>As part of its 40th anniversary celebrations the Foundation has launched a new website (www.medicalert.org.au) and is hosting a small celebration for invited guests in Adelaide on the evening of Monday 22 August.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Australian medical icon fit at 40',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2011-08-19','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:20:37','2016-10-03 02:51:45','2016-10-03 13:21:31'),(196,625,2,0,17,'Australian medical icon fit at 40',NULL,NULL,'australian-medical-icon-fit-at-40',0,'From its simple beginnings as a stainless steel bracelet, the widely recognised MedicAlert emblem provides a proven &lsquo;break-glass&rsquo; system protecting many thousands of Australians over the past 40 year','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>From its simple beginnings as a stainless steel bracelet, the widely recognised MedicAlert emblem provides a proven &lsquo;break-glass&rsquo; system protecting many thousands of Australians over the past 40 years.</p>\r\nThe 