ook on the wrist and around the neck for medical identification.</p>\r\n<p>Leading national health awareness and support organisations like Anaphylaxis Australia also recommend that children and adults at risk of anaphylaxis &ndash; the most severe form of allergic reaction &ndash; wear a MedicAlert emblem.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Time and time again our member parents report real benefits in using MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 service to protect their small children,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert puts parents in charge of their children&rsquo;s health over the holidays',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2011-07-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:23:19','2016-10-10 05:23:33',NULL),(199,627,2,0,17,'Back to school a time to be alert to children&rsquo;s medical conditions',NULL,NULL,'back-to-school-a-time-to-be-alert-to-childrenandrsquos-medical-conditions',0,'As parents prepare their children for the new school year, it&rsquo;s important to ensure any current medical conditions are well documented and that information is immediately available to teachers and ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>As parents prepare their children for the new school year, it&rsquo;s important to ensure any current medical conditions are well documented and that information is immediately available to teachers and emergency healthcare personnel.</p>\r\n<p>With rising rates of allergy, asthma and juvenile diabetes, thousands of Australian school children have a diagnosed medical condition, allergy or special need that can impact their care in the school and after-school settings.</p>\r\n<p>Statistics show that up to five per cent of children have a food allergy - most often to peanuts - by school age, one in nine school-aged children has asthma and about one in 700 children has diabetes.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation chief executive officer, Sandra Turner, said that in 2010, almost 13 percent of all new Foundation members nationally were children aged 12 years and under.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;During the school day a child may encounter a variety of situations that could result in the need for emergency care. It could be at recess, lunch, in the classroom, after school at a friend&rsquo;s house or during a sports activity,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Parents tell us that they want to ensure that their child&rsquo;s vital medical information is readily available and can be quickly and correctly communicated in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>The MedicAlert emblem is widely recognised and trusted by emergency healthcare professionals, and paramedics are trained to look on the wrist and around the neck for medical identification.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert emblem gives parents confidence and helps children to feel secure and safe wherever they are, while also helping the school community to recognise and manage students&rsquo; health issues,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>For more information, parents can contact the Australia Medic Alert Foundation on 1800 88 22 22.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Back to school a time to be alert to children&rsquo;s medical conditions',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2011-01-28','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:25:30','2016-10-10 05:18:39',NULL),(200,628,2,0,17,'Protecting your health over the holidays is no accident',NULL,NULL,'protecting-your-health-over-the-holidays-is-no-accident',0,'Christmas holidays signal an exodus of families heading to a favourite camping or fishing spot, to visit interstate relatives or an impromptu day at the beach.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Christmas holidays signal an exodus of families heading to a favourite camping or fishing spot, to visit interstate relatives or an impromptu day at the beach.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation Chief Executive Officer, Ms Sandra Turner, urges Australians to consider their health needs before they hit the road these holidays. &ldquo;While an unexpected accident or sudden illness is the last thing on holidaymakers&rsquo; minds, existing medical conditions like allergies, asthma, heart disease or diabetes don&#039;t take a break because you are,&rdquo; Ms Turner cautioned. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;Driver fatigue, unfamiliar surroundings, changes in diet and activity levels and exposure to different allergens or stinging insects can trigger a sudden medical emergency.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Quickly identifying a patient&rsquo;s underlying medical conditions can be vital to their survival in an emergency, particularly for children, whether visiting friends or relatives, playing in a caravan park or exploring new surroundings.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Emergency and medical personnel have only moments to determine a patient&rsquo;s specific needs and provide prompt, precise diagnosis and treatment in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.<br /> <br /> The genuine MedicAlert emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist has been protecting Australian lives for almost 40 years and is widely recognised and trusted by emergency healthcare professionals. <br /> <br /> Paramedics are trained to look for body-worn medical identification in an emergency and the genuine MedicAlert emblem has a member&rsquo;s critical medical and personal information engraved on the back. <br /> <br /> Emergency responders can also call MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on each emblem for more details about the patient including emergency contacts, allergies and medications, an important back-up service not usually offered by other medical identification providers.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Whether holidaying at home or away, wearing a custom engraved MedicAlert emblem gives families peace of mind that emergency personnel will always have access to vital medical information when seconds can count&rdquo;, Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Protecting your health over the holidays is no accident',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-12-20','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:27:15','2016-10-03 02:59:30','2016-10-03 13:29:16'),(201,628,2,0,17,'Protecting your health over the holidays is no accident',NULL,NULL,'protecting-your-health-over-the-holidays-is-no-accident',0,'Christmas holidays signal an exodus of families heading to a favourite camping or fishing spot, to visit interstate relatives or an impromptu day at the beach.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Christmas holidays signal an exodus of families heading to a favourite camping or fishing spot, to visit interstate relatives or an impromptu day at the beach.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation Chief Executive Officer, Ms Sandra Turner, urges Australians to consider their health needs before they hit the road these holidays. &ldquo;While an unexpected accident or sudden illness is the last thing on holidaymakers&rsquo; minds, existing medical conditions like allergies, asthma, heart disease or diabetes don&#039;t take a break because you are,&rdquo; Ms Turner cautioned. <br /> <br /> &ldquo;Driver fatigue, unfamiliar surroundings, changes in diet and activity levels and exposure to different allergens or stinging insects can trigger a sudden medical emergency.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Quickly identifying a patient&rsquo;s underlying medical conditions can be vital to their survival in an emergency, particularly for children, whether visiting friends or relatives, playing in a caravan park or exploring new surroundings.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Emergency and medical personnel have only moments to determine a patient&rsquo;s specific needs and provide prompt, precise diagnosis and treatment in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.<br /> <br /> The genuine MedicAlert emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist has been protecting Australian lives for almost 40 years and is widely recognised and trusted by emergency healthcare professionals. <br /> <br /> Paramedics are trained to look for body-worn medical identification in an emergency and the genuine MedicAlert emblem has a member&rsquo;s critical medical and personal information engraved on the back. <br /> <br /> Emergency responders can also call MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on each emblem for more details about the patient including emergency contacts, allergies and medications, an important back-up service not usually offered by other medical identification providers.<br /> <br /> &ldquo;Whether holidaying at home or away, wearing a custom engraved MedicAlert emblem gives families peace of mind that emergency personnel will always have access to vital medical information when seconds can count&rdquo;, Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Protecting your health over the holidays is no accident',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2010-12-20','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:27:15','2016-10-10 05:22:51',NULL),(202,629,2,0,17,'Medical identification helps people with diabetes take control, every day',NULL,NULL,'medical-identification-helps-people-with-diabetes-take-control-every-day',0,'Diabetes is Australia&rsquo;s fastest growing chronic disease. More than three million or one in four Australian adults over the age of 25 have either diabetes or impaired glucose tolerance (pre-diabetes).','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Diabetes is Australia&rsquo;s fastest growing chronic disease. More than three million or one in four Australian adults over the age of 25 have either diabetes or impaired glucose tolerance (pre-diabetes).</p>\r\n<p>On World Diabetes Day (14 November), the Australia Medic Alert Foundation reminds people with diabetes to wear well-recognised medical identification to avoid any guesswork in treating the potential complications of their disease in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>According to the Foundation&rsquo;s chief executive, Ms Sandra Turner, people with diabetes may be unable to communicate their special needs in a medical emergency due to confusion, coma or unconsciousness.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;They are also at higher risk of heart disease and stroke due to raised blood glucose levels, in association with high blood pressure and cholesterol,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Emergency and medical personnel have only moments to determine a patient&rsquo;s specific needs and provide prompt, precise diagnosis and treatment in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>The genuine MedicAlert emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist has been protecting the lives of Australians living with diabetes for almost 40 years and is widely recognised and trusted by emergency and healthcare professionals.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Paramedics are trained to look for medical identification around the neck or on the wrist in an emergency and the genuine MedicAlert emblem has a member&rsquo;s critical medical and personal information engraved on the back.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert supports emergency and healthcare personnel through an ongoing national education and awareness program,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>Emergency responders can also call MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on each emblem for more details about the patient including emergency contacts, allergies and medications &ndash; an important back-up service not offered by most other medical identification providers.</p>\r\n<p>Australian Diabetes Council Principal Health Strategy Executive, Dr Lilian Jackson, also urges people living with diabetes to wear an engraved medical identification.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People of all ages with diabetes should always wear or carry some identification stating that they have diabetes, particularly those on insulin, as they are at risk of hypoglycaemia and may require assistance from a second person.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It is best to wear a bracelet or a necklace but if that is not possible, at least carry an identification card. Most ambulance personnel will look at the person&rsquo;s neck or wrist for medical identification,&rdquo; said Dr Jackson.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert emblem as part of Foundation membership helps to ensure people with diabetes receive faster, safer treatment and can help to avoid a potentially serious outcome,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Medical identification helps people with diabetes take control, every day',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-11-12','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:29:55','2016-10-03 03:01:57','2016-10-03 13:31:43'),(203,629,2,0,17,'Medical identification helps people with diabetes take control, every day',NULL,NULL,'medical-identification-helps-people-with-diabetes-take-control-every-day',0,'Diabetes is Australia&rsquo;s fastest growing chronic disease. More than three million or one in four Australian adults over the age of 25 have either diabetes or impaired glucose tolerance (pre-diabetes).','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Diabetes is Australia&rsquo;s fastest growing chronic disease. More than three million or one in four Australian adults over the age of 25 have either diabetes or impaired glucose tolerance (pre-diabetes).</p>\r\n<p>On World Diabetes Day (14 November), the Australia Medic Alert Foundation reminds people with diabetes to wear well-recognised medical identification to avoid any guesswork in treating the potential complications of their disease in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>According to the Foundation&rsquo;s chief executive, Ms Sandra Turner, people with diabetes may be unable to communicate their special needs in a medical emergency due to confusion, coma or unconsciousness.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;They are also at higher risk of heart disease and stroke due to raised blood glucose levels, in association with high blood pressure and cholesterol,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Emergency and medical personnel have only moments to determine a patient&rsquo;s specific needs and provide prompt, precise diagnosis and treatment in an emergency,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p>The genuine MedicAlert emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist has been protecting the lives of Australians living with diabetes for almost 40 years and is widely recognised and trusted by emergency and healthcare professionals.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Paramedics are trained to look for medical identification around the neck or on the wrist in an emergency and the genuine MedicAlert emblem has a member&rsquo;s critical medical and personal information engraved on the back.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert supports emergency and healthcare personnel through an ongoing national education and awareness program,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>Emergency responders can also call MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on each emblem for more details about the patient including emergency contacts, allergies and medications &ndash; an important back-up service not offered by most other medical identification providers.</p>\r\n<p>Australian Diabetes Council Principal Health Strategy Executive, Dr Lilian Jackson, also urges people living with diabetes to wear an engraved medical identification.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People of all ages with diabetes should always wear or carry some identification stating that they have diabetes, particularly those on insulin, as they are at risk of hypoglycaemia and may require assistance from a second person.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It is best to wear a bracelet or a necklace but if that is not possible, at least carry an identification card. Most ambulance personnel will look at the person&rsquo;s neck or wrist for medical identification,&rdquo; said Dr Jackson.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert emblem as part of Foundation membership helps to ensure people with diabetes receive faster, safer treatment and can help to avoid a potentially serious outcome,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Medical identification helps people with diabetes take control, every day',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2010-11-12','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:29:55','2016-10-10 05:26:40',NULL),(204,630,2,0,17,'MedicAlert can help people with asthma to &#039;breathe easier&#039;',NULL,NULL,'medicalert-can-help-people-with-asthma-to-breathe-easier',0,'Asthma is one of Australia&rsquo;s most common chronic health problems affecting around two million people &ndash; one in nine children and one in 10 adults currently have the disease.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Asthma is one of Australia&rsquo;s most common chronic health problems affecting around two million people &ndash; one in nine children and one in 10 adults currently have the disease.</p>\r\n<p>Asthma is the most common chronic illness in children and those aged 0-14 are the group most likely to go to an emergency department for treatment.</p>\r\n<p>During National Asthma Week (1-7 September), the Australia Medic Alert Foundation reminds all Australians that quick action is vital in treating a sudden asthma attack.</p>\r\n<p>According to the Foundation&rsquo;s chief executive, Ms Sandra Turner, an asthma attack may be caused by exposure to a range of environmental &lsquo;triggers&rsquo;, including dust mites, pollens, cigarette smoke, strong smells such as perfume, some foods and preservatives and changes in the weather.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;As people don&rsquo;t always know what sets off their asthma and can&rsquo;t predict an attack, they risk being unprepared to manage serious and potentially life-threatening symptoms like severe shortness of breath,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>The MedicAlert emblem worn on the neck or wrist is instantly recognised by emergency personnel and healthcare professionals who are trained to look for key medical conditions such as asthma and medications engraved on the back.</p>\r\n<p>Emergency responders can also call MedicAlert&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on the emblem for more details about the patient. This may include medical conditions, emergency contacts, allergies, and medications, all stored in a secure national database.</p>\r\n<p>SA Ambulance Service Executive Director Clinical Services, Dr Hugh Grantham, said that in the event of a severe asthma attack, it is vital to call triple zero (000) sooner rather than later.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The ambulance service is here for you when you need us. We are able to provide life saving advice, treatment and transport to hospital if required.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We always look for MedicAlert emblems when the patient is unable to tell us what is happening, as can be the case with a severe asthma attack,&rdquo; said Dr Grantham.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert emblem as part of Foundation membership gives people with asthma the confidence to live their lives to the fullest without worrying about sharing their medical information in a medical emergency &ndash; helping to ensure they receive faster, safer treatment,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'MedicAlert can help people with asthma to &#039;breathe easier&#039;',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2010-09-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:32:22','2016-10-10 05:25:53',NULL),(205,631,2,0,17,'&#039;Grey Nomads&#039; urged to be more alert to their health needs',NULL,NULL,'grey-nomads-urged-to-be-more-alert-to-their-health-needs',0,'Many older Australians or so-called &lsquo;grey nomads&rsquo; who hit the road north to escape winter&rsquo;s chill, may be poorly prepared for travel in remote Australia, where distances span thousands of kilometres.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Many older Australians or so-called &lsquo;grey nomads&rsquo; who hit the road north to escape winter&rsquo;s chill, may be poorly prepared for travel in remote Australia, where distances span thousands of kilometres.</p>\r\n<p>A survey of 260 travellers to the Kimberley, Western Australia, published in Australian Family Physician in 2006 showed that many older visitors to the region had long term health problems. Almost 70 per cent of those aged over 65 had chronic health problems such as high blood pressure, heart disease, high cholesterol and diabetes and lung disease &ndash; and only half had enough medication to last their journey.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation chief executive officer, Sandra Turner, said that failing to take regular medication, changes in temperature, diet and activity levels and contact with different allergens, could trigger a sudden medical emergency.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Quickly identifying a patient&rsquo;s underlying medical conditions can be vital to their survival in an emergency, particularly if they are camping in a remote location with limited access to specialist services or if travelling alone,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>The survey also showed that only 19 per cent of travellers carried a list of regular medication they had been prescribed and fewer than 10 per cent had a summary of their medical health from their doctor.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;An individually engraved MedicAlert emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist is instantly recognised by emergency personnel and other health care professionals right across Australia.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Emergency healthcare providers can immediately check for key medical conditions, and quickly access more detailed information by calling the 24-hour emergency hotline number engraved on the emblem,&rdquo; said Ms Turner.</p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert members also receive a wallet card that gives more detailed information about their medical conditions, medications and emergency contacts.</p>\r\n<p>Dr John Setchell, General Manager of Health Services with Royal Flying Doctor Service Central Operations (RFDS), said up to one quarter of the emergency aeromedical evacuations carried out by the RFDS each year are the result of city travellers who become ill or critically injured on their Outback adventure.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People planning a winter escape need to take the precaution of having medical check-ups and filling prescriptions before leaving home,&rdquo; Dr Setchell said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Those with chronic disease should also carry a written health summary to assist local health service or RFDS personnel in managing their care, supported by wearing a MedicAlert emblem to help ensure the best possible medical response.&rdquo;</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'&#039;Grey Nomads&#039; urged to be more alert to their health needs',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-07-26','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:35:20','2016-10-03 03:07:07','2016-10-03 13:36:53'),(206,631,2,0,17,'&#039;Grey Nomads&#039; urged to be more alert to their health needs',NULL,NULL,'grey-nomads-urged-to-be-more-alert-to-their-health-needs',0,'Many older Australians or so-called &lsquo;grey nomads&rsquo; who hit the road north to escape winter&rsquo;s chill, may be poorly prepared for travel in remote Australia, where distances span thousands of kilometres.','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>Many older Australians or so-called &lsquo;grey nomads&rsquo; who hit the road north to escape winter&rsquo;s chill, may be poorly prepared for travel in remote Australia, where distances span