 out by the RFDS each year are the result of city travellers who become ill or critically injured on their Outback adventure.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People planning a winter escape need to take the precaution of having medical check-ups and filling prescriptions before leaving home,&rdquo; Dr Setchell said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Those with chronic disease should also carry a written health summary to assist local health service or RFDS personnel in managing their care, supported by wearing a MedicAlert emblem to help ensure the best possible medical response.&rdquo;</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'&#039;Grey Nomads&#039; urged to be more alert to their health needs',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2010-07-26','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:35:20','2016-10-10 05:15:51',NULL),(207,632,2,0,17,'Medical ID vital for people with diabetes in an emergency',NULL,NULL,'medical-id-vital-for-people-with-diabetes-in-an-emergency',0,'During National Diabetes Week (July 11-17), the Australia Medic Alert Foundation reminds all Australians that quick action is vital in treating the potential complications of diabetes in an emergency.','<p>During National Diabetes Week (July 11-17), the Australia Medic Alert Foundation reminds all Australians that quick action is vital in treating the potential complications of diabetes in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>Diabetes is on the march in Australia with over 800,000 people currently diagnosed with the disease and an estimated 275 people diagnosed each day, according to Diabetes Australia.</p>\r\n<p>A report published by the Australian Institute of Health and Welfare, Australia&rsquo;s Health 2010, also indicates that the rate of new cases of Type 1 diabetes among children under 15 years of age increased by 30 per cent between 2000 and 2007 and many people with Type 2 diabetes remain undiagnosed.</p>\r\n<p>Aside from the risk of hypo and hyperglycaemia, people with diabetes can develop chronic kidney disease, nerve damage, loss of vision and can also be at higher risk of coronary heart disease and stroke.</p>\r\n<p>According to the Foundation&rsquo;s chief executive, Ms Sandra Turner, people with diabetes may be unable to communicate their special needs in a medical emergency due to confusion or unconsciousness related to their diabetes.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Emergency and medical personnel have only moments to determine a patient&rsquo;s specific needs and to begin potentially lifesaving care in a diabetes emergency,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>An engraved MedicAlert&reg; emblem worn around the neck or on the wrist as part of a diabetes management plan can be instantly recognised by emergency personnel and healthcare professionals, providing critical information such as key medical conditions and current medications.</p>\r\n<p>As part of the MedicAlert&reg; system, emergency responders can call the Foundation&rsquo;s 24/7 emergency hotline number engraved on the back of the emblem to access further information about the patient. This may include other medical conditions, emergency contact details, allergies and more.</p>\r\n<p>Diabetes Australia advises people living with diabetes to wear medical identification to ensure that others know they are in need of urgent medical help particularly in the event of hypoglycaemia (when blood glucose levels fall too low) which can leave them unconscious, drowsy or unable to swallow.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Wearing a MedicAlert&reg; emblem as part of Foundation membership gives people living with diabetes the freedom to live their lives to the fullest without worrying about sharing medical information in a medical emergency. This helps to ensure they receive faster, safer treatment and avoid harmful or fatal reactions,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Medical ID vital for people with diabetes in an emergency',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2010-07-12','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:37:30','2016-10-10 05:21:35',NULL),(208,633,2,0,17,'Australians more alert to rise in food allergy',NULL,NULL,'australians-more-alert-to-rise-in-food-allergy',0,'The last decade has seen a rapid rise in the number of Australians suffering from potentially life threatening food allergies, now estimated to affect approximately six per cent of children and two ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>The largest increase in food allergy is amongst Australian children under the age of five years, with up to five per cent developing a food allergy by school age.</p>\r\n<p>According to Anaphylaxis Australia it is estimated that peanut allergy affects two to three per cent of children by school age, which for 80 per cent will remain a lifelong problem.</p>\r\n<p>Australia Medic Alert Foundation chief executive officer, Sandra Turner, said that the Foundation&rsquo;s membership reflects this rise in allergies, particularly amongst children.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In 2009 almost 13 per cent of all new MedicAlert&reg; members nationally were children aged 12 years and under &ndash; many due to food allergy,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It can be difficult for parents to cope with managing a severe allergy in young children; however, there are practical solutions to reduce the risk of living with allergies.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>During Food Allergy Awareness Week (May 16-22), MedicAlert&reg; reminds all Australians that quick action is vital in treating the potentially life threatening severe allergic reaction (anaphylaxis) that can result from food allergy.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Almost 150,000 Australians currently benefit from the MedicAlert&reg; system and we continue to urge all people with hidden medical conditions like food allergy to consider taking advantage of the 24-hour protection it offers,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>Anaphylaxis Australia advises that all people who are at risk of anaphylaxis have a sound action plan and carry their adrenaline auto-injector at all times. They also recommend people at risk wear medical identification in case they are not with people who know of their condition and know what to do in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The MedicAlert&reg; emblem worn around the neck or wrist is widely recognised by emergency personnel and other health care professionals who can immediately check for important medical conditions or allergies, a personal ID number and the 24-hour emergency number engraved on the emblem,&rdquo; Ms Turner said.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It is important that young people with allergies are not excluded from activities and have the freedom to live life as normally as possible. Wearing a MedicAlert&reg; emblem as part of Australia Medic Alert Foundation membership brings peace of mind to both the sufferer and their family, particularly as they become more independent at school, playing sport and socially,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Australians more alert to rise in food allergy',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-05-14','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-03 13:38:54','2016-10-03 03:10:59','2016-10-03 13:40:46'),(209,633,2,0,17,'Australians more alert to rise in food allergy',NULL,NULL,'australians-more-alert-to-rise-in-food-allergy',0,'The last decade has seen a rapid rise in the number of Australians suffering from potentially life threatening food allergies, now estimated to affect approximately six per cent of children and two ','<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p>The largest increase in food allergy is amongst Australian children under the age of five years, with up to five per cent developing a food allergy by school age.</p>\r\n<p>According to Anaphylaxis Australia it is estimated that peanut allergy affects two to three per cent of children by school a