our Will. You can:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;><strong>Include the whole or a percentage of the remainder of your estate</strong> (known as the residue). The residue of your estate is what remains of the estate once your debts are paid and specific gifts are distributed to your loved ones named in your will. A residuary gift could be a percentage or the whole of the residue of your estate.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;><strong>You can leave your entire estate or a percentage of your estate</strong> to MedicAlert Foundation.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;><strong>Leave a fixed sum of money</strong>, also known as a pecuniary gift. This gift is in the form of a specified cash amount.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;><strong>Include a specific item or gift</strong>. You may wish to leave us a gift in the form of other property.</li>\r\n</ul>','<h3 style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Would you like help with wording for your will?</h3>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>We have put together some suggested wording should you wish to include the MedicAlert Foundation in your Will. Please note we recommend the form of words to be used in your Will should be confirmed by your solicitor or other legal counsel. Please find the suggested wording below:</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>I give </strong><strong>to the Australia Medic Alert Foundation (ACN 050 542 455)</strong> <strong>for its general purposes<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Choose and insert as desired one or more of the following:</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>The whole </strong>(or insert the percentage number) <strong>residue of my estate</strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>The whole </strong>(or insert the percentage number) <strong>of my estate </strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>A fixed monetary amount</strong> (insert the value of your gift in cash)</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Or (insert details of a specified item) <strong>item<br /><br /> </strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>AND </strong><strong>the receipt of the treasurer, secretary or public officer for the time being of the beneficiary under this clause is an absolute discharge to my Executors.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;> </p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>In preparation of your Will, the following information regarding the MedicAlert Foundation should be given to the drafter of your Will:</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>ABN 31 140 801 427</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>GPO Box 9963, Adelaide SA 5001</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Endorsed as an income tax exempt charitable entry</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Endorsed as a deductible gift recipient</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Endorsed for GST concessions</p>','<h3 style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>Contact Us</h3>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;> </p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>If you have any questions about leaving a gift or bequest to the MedicAlert Foundation, please call our Membership Services team on <a href=&quot;1800 88 22 22&quot;>1800 88 22 22</a> (8:30am &ndash; 5:30pm AEST).</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Gifts to the MedicAlert Foundation in your Will | MedicAlert',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/donate-banner.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-11 11:42:34','2016-10-26 06:46:38',NULL),(232,664,1,0,0,'Thank you for taking a survey','Thank you',NULL,'thank-you-for-taking-a-survey',0,'<p>Thank you for submitting your feedback. If you have requested someone from MedicAlert contact you about your response, you can expect to be contacted within 48 hours.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Thank you for taking our survey | MedicAlert',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-11 16:28:23','2016-10-26 06:47:29',NULL),(233,665,1,0,0,'Login',NULL,NULL,'login',0,'<p>All MedicAlert jewellery is backed by a vital MedicAlert membership. When you become a member, you&rsquo;re taking control of your health by ensuring you&rsquo;ll receive fast and effective treatment in an emergency. MedicAlert members also receive access to a range of exclusive <a href=&quot;/benefits-of-membership&quot;>member-only benefits</a>.<br /><br /></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,99,'Login - MedicAlert Foundation Australia | MedicAlert','Log in to the MedicAlert Member&#039;s Area here to view your membership profile, renew your membership or purchase a new product.',NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-12 21:04:54','2016-10-26 06:10:33',NULL),(234,666,1,0,0,'test',NULL,NULL,'test',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'test',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 12:16:24','2016-10-13 09:16:08','2016-10-13 19:46:08'),(235,667,10,1,6,'Bupa member',NULL,NULL,'bupa-member',0,'<p>Exclusive Bupa member offer: 2 year MedicAlert<sup>&reg;</sup> membership + one medical ID listed on this page of your choice* for just $100 and save up to 20%. </p>\r\n<p>If you&#039;re a Bupa member, please use discount code <strong>BUPA16</strong> during the checkout.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,9999,'Special Offer for Bupa Members | MedicAlert','If you&#039;re a Bupa member, you can save up to 20% on a 2 year MedicAlert membership plus a medical ID of your choice. Great for people living with medical conditions and allergies. Redeem this special offer now.',NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,1,'2016-10-13 15:29:31','2016-10-26 05:29:13',NULL),(236,670,6,0,0,'Bupa',NULL,NULL,'bupa',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>*Selected products only. Price includes standard postage and handling and a 12-month standard Australia MedicAlert Foundation product warranty.</p>',NULL,'BUPA18',667,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Bupa',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:05:05','2017-12-19 05:49:02',NULL),(237,672,2,0,17,'10 foods that could save your heart',NULL,NULL,'10-foods-that-could-save-your-heart',0,NULL,'<h1> </h1>\r\n<p>With so many industries, organisations and individuals telling you what you should be eating, it&rsquo;s hard to know what&rsquo;s truly good for your heart. It&rsquo;s not uncommon to hear that the same food that can solve heart disease according to one organisation might also cause heart issues according to another. So what&rsquo;s the truth?</p>\r\n<p>Well, as it stands heart disease is the leading cause of death in Australia, but with a healthy blend of exercise, the right lifestyle choices (no smoking) and a balanced diet packed full of the following foods you can make sure you don&rsquo;t add to this statistic.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h3><strong>1. SALMON</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Salmon and other oily fish such as sardines and mackerel are the superstars of heart-healthy foods. That&#039;s because they contain large amounts of omega-3 fatty acids, which have been shown to slow the build up of artery-clogging plaque, lower blood triglyceride levels, reduce the risk of irregular heartbeats, and lower blood pressure. The National Heart Foundation of Australia recommends eating 2-3 serves of fish a week (100-150g per serve).</p>\r\n<p><br /><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/salmon.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;salmon.jpg (85 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /><br /><br /></p>\r\n<h3><strong>2. BLUEBERRIES</strong></h3>\r\n<p>The brighter the better. All colurful fruits and vegetables contain phytonutrients and offer health benefits, but dark-skinned blueberries are especially high in disease-fighting antioxidants that can help prevent heart disease.</p>\r\n<p><strong><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/blueberry.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;blueberry.jpg (64 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /><br /><br />3. OATS</strong></p>\r\n<p>Oats are high in soluble fibre, which can lower cholesterol. Soluble fibre acts like a sponge in the digestive tract and soaks up the cholesterol so it is eliminated from the body and not absorbed into the bloodstream. Tip: Try avoiding instant oats, which often contain sugar, and look instead for old-fashioned or even quick-cooking oats.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/oats.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;oats.jpg (89 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />4. BLACK BEANS</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Beans and other legumes are rich in protein, high in soluble fibre, and contain no saturated fat. Enjoy any variety of beans, chickpeas, or lentils, but black beans get extra points for heart-healthy antioxidants. Tip: Use beans instead of beef for your next Mexican feast.</p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/blackbeans.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;blackbeans.jpg (91 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /> </p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />5. WALNUTS</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Nuts are a great source of healthy fats, antioxidants, and fibre. A small handful of nuts makes a great snack once a day and will help you to reduce the risk of developing heart disease. Walnuts are the highest in omega-3s, but almonds, hazelnuts, and pistachios are also healthy and tasty choices.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/walnut.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;walnut.jpg (79 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />6. KALE</strong></h3>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re into healthy foods you&rsquo;ve probably heard of the term &lsquo;kale&rsquo; and for good reason. The dark crinkled leaves contain antioxidants, fibre, and a range of valuable vitamins and minerals that have been shown to support heart health. Don&rsquo;t like kale? Spinach, beet greens, Swiss chard, turnip greens, and collards are good for you too.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/kale.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;kale.jpg (104 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />7. AVOCADO</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Avocadoes are a great alternative to traditional spreads like butter. Each avocado is packed with over 14 minerals, 18 essential amino acids (protein) and more potassium than a banana, which can help regulate blood pressure. They also contain monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats, folate and fibre, making it a heart-healthy powerhouse. Tip: Use avocado on your sandwich instead of butter or mayonnaise.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/avocado.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;avocado.jpg (108 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />8.</strong> <strong>EXTRA-VIRGIN OLIVE OIL</strong></h3>\r\n<p>There are endless healthy reasons to make extra-virgin olive oil your first choice for cooking. To begin with, olive oil contains monounsaturated &lsquo;good fats&rsquo; that can help reduce your LDL cholesterol levels. Extra-virgin varieties also contain antioxidants, for an added pick me up.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/olivoil.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;olivoil.jpg (87 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<h3><strong><br />9. TOFU</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Tofu, made from soybean curds, is naturally gluten-free, low in calories, contains no cholesterol and is an excellent source of protein, iron, and calcium. Countless studies have suggested that increasing consumption of plant-based foods like tofu, decreases the risk of obesity, diabetes, heart disease and promotes a healthy complexion and hair, increased energy, and overall lower weight &ndash; all of which are great for your heart. Tip: Use tofu in the place of meat once a week.</p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/tofo.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;tofo.jpg (89 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /></p>\r\n<p><strong><br />10. WHOLE GRAIN BREAD</strong></p>\r\n<p>Scrap white bread (which is often full of sugar and salt) and choose something packed full of grains and linseeds - which are a great source of healthy fats. Eating grain foods, mostly wholegrains, can help protect against heart disease and other chronic diseases, like type 2 diabetes and some cancers. We also recommend choosing breads lower in salt, which is listed as sodium in the nutrition information panel on food labels. Check the per 100g column in the panel, and choose breads with sodium of 400mg or less per 100g, and fibre of 4g or more per 100g.</p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/bread.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;bread.jpg (81 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>For more information, tips and heart healthy recipes visit <a href=&quot;http://heartfoundation.org.au/healthy-eating&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>http://heartfoundation.org.au/healthy-eating<br /><br /><br /></a><a href=&quot;http://heartfoundation.org.au/healthy-eating&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;><br /></a></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'10 foods that could save your heart',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:50:05','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(238,673,2,0,17,'Does the coach know?',NULL,NULL,'does-the-coach-know',0,NULL,'<h1> </h1>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/coach.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;coach.jpg (97 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; />It&rsquo;s that time of year where you&rsquo;re probably running from shop to shop trying to find the right boots, bibs and balls for the winter sports season. This means it&rsquo;s also a great time to remind your coach of any pre-existing medical conditions, allergies or medications &ndash; the type you might list on your MedicAlert medical ID &ndash; because the more people that know how to treat you in an emergency, the safer you&rsquo;ll be.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>A great way to ensure your coach or team manager is aware of your relevant medical history is to provide them with a copy of your wallet card. Describe what the wallet card does and that emergency services need to be made aware of this information in an emergency situation.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>And remember, while sport is a great way to keep fit and healthy, it also provides a few additional dangers you should be aware of. Firstly, your chances of becoming unconscious and unable to speak in an emergency are increased, with pain, exhaustion or concussion often leading to a lack of consciousness. Added to this is the fact that you&rsquo;ll often be asked to remove your MedicAlert jewellery prior to a game to avoid injuring yourself or other players, so it becomes even more important to make sure your coach or team manager is aware of your medical history.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong><em>And don&rsquo;t forget, if you do take off your medical ID before each game; remember to put it back on afterwards.</em></strong></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>So, as you rush to get that last minute sports shopping done we wish you good luck for the season ahead &ndash; let&rsquo;s make sure it&rsquo;s a safe one.<br /><br /><br /></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Does the coach know?',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:51:47','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(239,674,2,0,17,'Our new best seller',NULL,NULL,'our-new-best-seller',0,NULL,'<h1> </h1>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/steel_wristband_tag_h_on_activity_tracker_black_mar16_copy1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;steel_wristband_tag_h_on_activity_tracker_black_mar16_copy1.jpg (786 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;199&quot; />Exercise is important, and we know that a short run, evening stroll or gut-wrenching gym workout can help with a number of medical conditions we see our members living with, so in March this year we released a new silicone wristband tag that will keep you safe while you get your sweat on.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The new all-purpose emblem style is designed to provide you with protection and peace of mind no matter where you may wish to walk, run, climb or hike. Simply attach your customised medical ID wristband tag to your watch or activity tracker and enjoy the comfort of knowing you&rsquo;ll be covered by the genuine MedicAlert emblem wherever you are. A perfect addition to the Garmin vivofit available in our current member offer.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The new <a href=&quot;https://www.medicalert.org.au/Products&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>silicone wristband tags</a> come in two sizes (small and large) and two colours (black and white) and are available for only $35. Please note that the design of the wristband tags means that they are not flippable, asall information is on the front of the medical ID.</p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/new_tag.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;new_tag.jpg (36 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /><br /><br /><br /></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Our new best seller',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:53:55','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(240,675,2,0,17,'Stop heart attacks in their tracks',NULL,NULL,'stop-heart-attacks-in-their-tracks',0,NULL,'<h1> </h1>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/heartweek.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;heartweek.jpg (31 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; />During Heart Week (1-7 May 2016), the Heart Foundation is talking about how attending a cardiac rehabilitation program after a heart attack is a critical first step in a person&rsquo;s recovery and the best way to help prevent having another one. Studies show that heart attack survivors who have participated in a cardiac rehabilitation program have a greater chance of avoiding a second event. In fact they are 40% less likely to be readmitted to hospital and 25% less likely to die from another heart attack.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;p1&quot;>So this Heart Week, have a conversation with your doctor, and call the Heart Foundation Health Information Service on 1300 36 27 87 &ndash; they can help you find your local cardiac rehabilitation program.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;p1&quot;>And remember, if you are suffering from a heart condition, please speak to your doctor about how MedicAlert can help keep you safe in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;p1&quot;> </p>\r\n<p class=&quot;p2&quot;><span class=&quot;s1&quot;>For more information visit <a href=&quot;http://www.heartfoundation.org.au/heartweek&quot;>www.heartfoundation.org.au/heartweek<br /></a><br /></span></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Stop heart attacks in their tracks',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:56:12','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(241,676,2,0,17,'Speak for yourself',NULL,NULL,'speak-for-yourself',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/speak_for_yourself2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;speak_for_yourself2.jpg (65 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; />While MedicAlert medical IDs are largely there to help keep you safe in any emergency that may render you unable to communicate, if you find yourself in an emergency where you are able to speak you should always advise treating healthcare professionals that your medical information is kept on file through MedicAlert, who also offer a 24/7 Emergency Response Service should they need to contact us.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>If you are conscious when paramedics reach you, we would advise you to show them your medical ID and hand them your wallet card, both of which will allow them to access your full medical and personal information available on your personal file. If you are having communication issues due to anxiety, swollen airways or for any other reason remember to point to your medical ID. These actions will help ensure paramedics are aware of your conditions and they don&rsquo;t miss anything when deciding on the best possible treatment.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>And of course, if at any point you become unconscious during the course of the emergency or treatment the above course of action will ensure the treating paramedic knows how to access your full personal and medical information.<br /><br /><br /><br /></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Speak for yourself',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:58:33','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(242,677,2,0,17,'Cheat&rsquo;s Fish Pie',NULL,NULL,'cheats-fish-pie',0,NULL,'<p>It&rsquo;s Autumn, which for many will mean you&rsquo;ve felt the first chills of winter and you might be looking to heat up at night with a nice warm meal. So here&rsquo;s one of the tastiest and easiest ways to impress the guests (or family) while also keeping healthy &ndash; because as you&rsquo;ve no doubt read <a href=&quot;/news-and-resources/10-foods-that-could-save-your-heart&quot;>fish is the flavour of the month.</a></p>\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need around 25 minutes for prep and 15-20 minutes to cook, but it will be well worth the effort.</p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: left;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/fishpie.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;fishpie.jpg (39 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;182&quot; /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Ingredients</em></strong><br /><br />&middot; 4 (about 460g) skinless, boneless white fish fillets (eg. ling or dory)<br />&middot; Squeeze of lemon juice<br />&middot; 1/3 cup reduced fat spreadable cream cheese<br />&middot; 2 teaspoons Dijon mustard<br />&middot; 2 tablespoons chopped fresh chives<br />&middot; 1/2 teaspoon finely grated lemon rind<br />&middot; 4 sheets filo pastry<br />&middot; Olive oil spray<br />&middot; 1 teaspoon olive oil<br />&middot; 1 small clove garlic, crushed<br />&middot; 1 bunch English spinach, rinsed, stems trimmed<br />&middot; Boiled chat potatoes, to serve</p>\r\n<p>And remember look for the Heart Foundation Tick where possible.<br /><br /><strong><em>Method</em></strong><br /><br />1. Preheat oven to 190&deg;C (170&deg;C fan-forced).<br /><br />2. Lightly grease a shallow-sided, non-stick oven tray with cooking spray. Arrange the fish fillets in a single layer over the prepared tray and drizzle with a squeeze of lemon juice.<br /><br />3. Mix together the cream cheese, mustard, chives and lemon rind and spread mixture over fish fillets.<br /><br />4. Spray 1 filo sheet with cooking spray, fold in half, reapply cooking spray then fold in half again. Cut layered filo into quarters. Gently scrunch up the filo pieces, place over one fish fillet and reapply cooking spray. Repeat with remaining filo to cover all fish fillets.<br /><br />5. Bake in preheated oven for 15-20 minutes until filo is golden and fish is cooked through.<br /><br />6. Heat oil in a small non-stick frypan, add garlic, saut&eacute; briefly then add spinach and cook a further 1-2 minutes until spinach is just wilted.<br /><br />7. Divide the spinach between four dinner plates, top with fish fillets and serve with chat potatoes.</p>\r\n<p>Recipe and image reproduced with permission from the Heart Foundation website. &copy; 2016 National Heart Foundation of Australia. For more healthy recipes visit <a href=&quot;http://www.heartfoundation.org.au/recipes&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>www.heartfoundation.org.au/recipes</a> or speak to the Heart Foundation&rsquo;s Health Information Service on 1300 36 27 87.</p>\r\n<p> </p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Cheat&rsquo;s Fish Pie',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-04-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:59:35','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(243,678,2,0,17,'Our latest partnership could save your life',NULL,NULL,'our-latest-partnership-could-save-your-life',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/healthtrning.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;healthtrning.jpg (32 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;181&quot; />Australia Medic Alert Foundation has partnered with Flinders University in South Australia to launch a new training campaign aimed at ensuring all paramedic students are taught to look for medical IDs and wallet and fridge cards in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>As part of their on-the-job training, all Flinders University paramedic students are now being familiarised with how to look for MedicAlert medical IDs - through placing them on mannequins &ndash; and what the various details might mean in the event of treating that patient in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>One of the facilitators of this course said the Paramedic Unit at Flinders University was thrilled to be able to use MedicAlert material when teaching their students.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert is the foremost-recognised brand when it comes to alert identification for patients with allergies, medical issues and medications,&rdquo; said the facilitator.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;So it is important that our students are able to quickly identify these issues in both the unconscious and conscious patients and we find that MedicAlert products are both easily and readily identifiable in an emergency situation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>But students at Flinders University are not only trained on how to look for medical IDs, but also what to do when they find one.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;MedicAlert material is used both in lectures when teaching medical and trauma assessment and in practical simulations where students must treat patients in emergency situations.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>As part of our ongoing commitment to maintain our position as Australia&rsquo;s most recognised and trusted medical ID, we&rsquo;re not only educating the paramedics of tomorrow, but we&rsquo;ve also upgraded our educational material for current first responders, which will now include a new training video, training kit and educational poster.</p>\r\n<p>This program will be rolled out to other educators and trainers nationally.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Our latest partnership could save your life',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-06-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:02:16','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(244,679,2,0,17,'New interpreting service available',NULL,NULL,'new-interpreting-service-available',0,NULL,'<div id=&quot;article&quot; class=&quot;news-article&quot;>\r\n<div class=&quot;news-article-content&quot;>\r\n<div id=&quot;description&quot; class=&quot;news-description&quot;>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/interpreter.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;interpreter.jpg (43 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;181&quot; />Our goal at MedicAlert is to provide responsive personal medical identification and information to all Australians. As such, we have taken it upon ourselves to provide a free interpreting service for all members who call the member service hotline.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>To access this service simply call the member services team on <a href=&quot;1800 88 22 22&quot;>1800 88 22 22</a> and advise them of what language you require interpreting services for (have a friend help you if you need) and we&rsquo;ll arrange a time for an interpreter to call you back to discuss your needs.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<p> </p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'New interpreting service available',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-06-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:03:44','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(245,680,2,0,17,'We are going digital',NULL,NULL,'we-are-going-digital',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/noticephone.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;noticephone.jpg (48 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;181&quot; />MedicAlert is committed to providing the most efficient, user friendly and cost-effective services to its members. As such, we will be delivering all of your critical renewal notices and announcements via email, as of June this year.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>This new member benefit is aimed at helping to save time and the environment, by allowing you to renew online. While you&rsquo;re there please check that your personal and medical information is up to date.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>So please, if you aren&rsquo;t already, ensure you start looking out for your MedicAlert notices online.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'We are going digital',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-06-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:05:41','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(246,681,2,0,17,'You could help save lives',NULL,NULL,'you-could-help-save-lives',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/handsshot.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;handsshot.jpg (54 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;181&quot; />There is a quote we love to live by at MedicAlert and it is this &ldquo;together, anything is possible&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>See, the MedicAlert Foundation is a not-for-profit, member-based organisation that does not receive any government funding. As such, we rely not only on product sales, but also your generous support to ensure we can provide our vital service to every Australian who needs it.</p>\r\n<p>We know how critical it is to remain independent and member (not-profit) focussed, so we&rsquo;ve launched a donations initiative that can help ensure we can continue to provide this life-saving service to you.</p>\r\n<p>It is only with your help that we can continue to educate healthcare professionals about the importance of the MedicAlert Foundation and medical IDs, as well as keep member fees affordable for all.</p>\r\n<p>So, no matter how big or small, your donation will help us continue our mission to provide all Australians with essential medical protection when it counts.</p>\r\n<p>All donations $2.00 and over are tax deductible. To make a donation simply <a href=&quot;/donate&quot;>click here </a>and select your donation amount.</p>\r\n<p>You can also donate by calling us <a title=&quot;Click to call&quot; href=&quot;1800 88 22 22&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>1800 88 22 22</a> (Monday-Friday, 9am-5pm CST) or through these other creative ways:</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Gift Certificates</strong><strong><br /></strong>Give the gift of &lsquo;peace of mind, always&rsquo; - MedicAlert <a href=&quot;/gift-certificates&quot;>Gift Certificates </a>are ideal for every occasion (birthdays, Christmas, anniversary, Mother&rsquo;s/Father&rsquo;s Day).</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>In Memory</strong><strong><br /></strong>Remember a family member, friend or colleague and show your respect and support for others during their time of loss. The designated recipient will receive an acknowledgement of your gesture of sympathy. You will be mailed a charitable tax receipt (for gifts $2 and over) with a letter of appreciation from the MedicAlert Foundation.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'You could help save lives',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-06-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:07:01','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(247,682,2,0,17,'Mango chicken with sweet potato and pumpkin mash',NULL,NULL,'mango-chicken-with-sweet-potato-and-pumpkin-mash',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/mangochick.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;mangochick.jpg (102 KB)&quot; width=&quot;278&quot; height=&quot;271&quot; />Here&rsquo;s a beautiful and healthy winter warmer from &lsquo;Diabetic Living&rsquo; that&rsquo;s sure to leave you wanting more.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipehead&quot;><strong>Mango chicken with sweet potato and pumpkin mash</strong></p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipeprep&quot;>Preparation time: 15 mins</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipeprep&quot;>Cooking time: 30 mins</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipeprep&quot;>Serves 4 (as a main)</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipebody&quot;> </p>\r\n<p><strong>INGREDITENTS</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 tsp olive oil</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 tsp mustard seeds</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 tsp cumin seeds</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>12 fresh curry leaves</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 long green chilli, split lengthways</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>2 tsp ground turmeric</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>&frac12; x 685g container mango slices in juice, undrained</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>500g chicken tenderloins, sinew removed, halved crossways</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>130g (&frac12; cup) low-fat Greek-style plain yoghurt, whisked until smooth</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 tsp light margarine</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>2 Tbsp raisins</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1 Tbsp slivered almonds</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>1&frasl;4 cup coriander leaves, to serve</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;><strong>Sweet potato and pumpkin mash</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>650g sweet potato, chopped</li>\r\n<li class=&quot;recipeingred&quot;>700g pumpkin, chopped</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipebody&quot;><strong>1</strong> Heat oil in a large non-stick frying pan over a medium heat. Add mustard seeds, cumin seeds and curry leaves. Cook, stirring, for 2 minutes. Add chilli and turmeric and cook, stirring, for 1 minute. Add mango slices and juice. <br />Cover and cook for 10 minutes. Roughly mash with a potato masher. Add chicken and cook, stirring occasionally, for 5 minutes. Remove pan from heat and set aside, covered, for 15 minutes.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipebody&quot;><strong>2</strong> Meanwhile, to make mash, put sweet potato and pumpkin in a steamer basket over a saucepan of simmering water. Cover and steam for 20 minutes or until very tender. Transfer to a large bowl. Mash until smooth.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipebody&quot;><strong>3</strong> Stir yoghurt into chicken mixture. Return pan to a low heat and cook, stirring, for 5 minutes or until warmed through. Do not allow sauce to simmer or it will separate.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;recipebody&quot;><strong>4</strong> Heat margarine in a small non-stick frying pan over a medium heat. Add raisins and almonds and cook, stirring often, for 4-5 minutes or until raisins are plump and almonds are light golden brown. Divide mash between serving plates. Sprinkle over raisin mixture. Add chicken, sprinkle over coriander and serve.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p class=&quot;perservehead&quot;><strong>Nutrition Info</strong></p>\r\n<p class=&quot;perservingbold&quot;>PER SERVE 1911kJ, protein 37g, total fat 7.4g (sat. fat 1.7g), carbs 55g, fibre 9g, sodium 114mg.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;perservingbold&quot;>&bull; Carb exchanges 3 2&frasl;3.</p>\r\n<p class=&quot;perservingbold&quot;>&bull; GI estimate low.</p>\r\n<p>&bull; Gluten free.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Mango chicken with sweet potato and pumpkin mash',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-06-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:08:54','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(248,683,2,0,17,'Defeating allergies this spring',NULL,NULL,'defeating-allergies-this-spring',0,NULL,'<p>It&rsquo;s a beautiful time of year as the days grow longer and the weather heats up, but for some, spring also means runny noses, itchy eyes, sneezing fits and sometimes much worse. So how can allergy sufferers stay safe and avoid missing out on socialising outdoors?</p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; title=&quot;allergy&quot; src=&quot;https://www.medicalert.org.au/uploads/News/images/allergy_shot.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;allergy&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; height=&quot;334&quot; /></p>\r\n<p>7. <strong>Know your enemy.</strong> Pollen is the most common cause of increased allergy activity in spring, with around 15% of Australians suffering hayfever during this period. So what exactly is pollen? Pollen is the microscopic grains produced by the male parts of the plant when it flowers. These tiny particles are typically released in the morning and are spread by birds, bees or wind, in order to reproduce.</p>\r\n<p>Pollen and other &#039;allergens&#039;, irritate the lining of the sensitive nasal passages, inflaming them and causing them to secrete fluids. They can also cause other allergic conditions like watery eyes, itchiness and asthma.</p>\r\n<p><br />6. <strong>Which plants produce the most pollen?</strong> While we may notice them more, most beautiful and bright flowering plants (like the infamous wattle) actually don&rsquo;t need to produce as much pollen because it is often carried to other plants by birds and bees, where as other more common plants such as grasses produce huge amounts of pollen because they rely on wind to spread it.</p>\r\n<p><br />The Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy says the most significant causes of hayfever during spring in the southern states are temperate grasses - particularly ryegrass, which can affect people who are a long way from the source.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>5. <strong>Know if it is a cold or an allergy.</strong> Hayfever, another term for allergic rhinitis, commonly presents itself like a cold or the flu, which can be confusing since the spring allergy season and flu season overlap. However, there is a definite distinction between these conditions. In general, allergy symptoms kick in fast (as opposed to over the course of a few days), linger for longer than a week, don&rsquo;t include fever and aches, and involve a runny nose with clear mucus. Allergies cannot be cured, but they can be treated in numerous ways, such as taking over-the-counter and prescription medications, minimising contact with allergens, and managing one&rsquo;s environment.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>4. <strong>Clean, clean, clean.</strong> Common everyday items are the most likely things to trigger an allergic reaction, which means cleaning everything from your clothes to your bed sheets is critical to avoiding reactions. Tricks such as adding bicarbonate of soda or vinegar to the washing machine to get rid of excess detergent residue can be helpful, while investing in dust mite covers for your bed and pillows is a must. If possible, also consider making your bedroom a pet-free zone and replace carpets with hardwood floors.</p>\r\n<p><br />3. <strong>Utilise technology. </strong>Like the weather, allergies also have a forecast, and these days there are a number of useful apps and websites that can help you track and manage your allergies before they really flare up. Both the Weather Zone Pollen Index <a href=&quot;http://www.weatherzone.com.au/pollen-index/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>website</a> and <a href=&quot;https://itunes.apple.com/au/app/weatherzone/id409060691?mt=8&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>APP</a>, as well as <a href=&quot;http://www.accuweather.com/en/au/australia-weather&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>accuweather.com</a>(via their allergies tab) offer great insights into the daily pollen count and other useful facts.</p>\r\n<p><br />2. <strong>Changing your daily routine.</strong> If your allergies are triggered by seasonal changes, such as more exposure to plant pollen in the spring or additional mould and dust mites in winter, then you may need to change with the seasons. Basically, you want to reduce your exposure to the allergens when they&rsquo;re at their peak and remove them from your environment as much as possible. This may include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Only going outdoors after 11am (or at low pollen times indicated by the above apps).</li>\r\n<li>Changing your clothes and shoes when you walk through the door so you don&rsquo;t bring allergens into the house.</li>\r\n<li>Dusting early in the day to give dust time to settle before you settle down in the evening.</li>\r\n<li>Showering at night to get rid of the pollen you&rsquo;ve picked up all day so you&rsquo;re not breathing it in all night long.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Before we get to number one&hellip;</strong> did you know that MedicAlert has been recognised and recommended by the World Allergy Organisation as a valuable preventative tool to use to support your allergies and alert service to speak for you in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>1. <strong>Knowledge is power.</strong> The most important first step is to find out exactly what you&rsquo;re allergic to, otherwise you simply won&rsquo;t be able to treat it and you&rsquo;ll keep suffering. Try keeping a journal so you can pinpoint your allergy triggers, whether it&rsquo;s environmental (a certain tree, road or building) or a specific food. And remember, while there are some over the counter medications that may work for some, if symptoms persist see your GP or get tested by an allergist.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Defeating allergies this spring',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-08-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:13:42','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(249,684,2,0,17,'Better than the rest',NULL,NULL,'better-than-the-rest',0,NULL,'<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/medicalertbracelet.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;medicalertbracelet.jpg (16 KB)&quot; width=&quot;290&quot; height=&quot;181&quot; />You may never see her, but chances are that if you are caught in a medical emergency and you&rsquo;re wearing your MedicAlert medical ID, then Dr Sarah LePage&rsquo;s expertise could be the difference between life and death.</p>\r\n<p>As our resident clinical expert, Dr LePage assist to ensure that all our engraving meets standard abbreviations and best practice in healthcare communication, General Practitioner Dr LePage says it is critical to have such quality control processes in place.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;What use is a MedicAlert bracelet if it doesn&rsquo;t have the correct description of a condition or if the wording is not easily understood by emergency responders!?&rdquo; says Dr LePage.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s my job to oversee what people are engraving on their medical ID&rsquo;s and to make sure that MedicAlert&rsquo;s membership services staff and all emergency and healthcare professionals understand exactly what those engravings mean.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>While other medical identification organisations allow their members to engrave anything they want, Dr LePage says she is proud to work with an organisation that is committed to ensuring that even a member of the public can understand and act on engravings.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;If someone is lost and wondering in the street and suddenly you see on their bracelet that they have &lsquo;Dementia&rsquo;, memory loss and &lsquo;Contact details&rsquo; listed on their medical ID, then suddenly anyone can act on that situation and help protect that person,&rdquo; says Dr LePage.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I guess my other focus is ensuring that MedicAlert membership services staff are also aware of standard medical abbreviations, and also rare conditions and engravings we are confronted with from time to time. Because at the end of the day this level of quality control is what keeps people safe and can give true peace of mind to members.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>While we can&rsquo;t always avoid an emergency, Dr LePage says it is reassuring to know that first responders are also being taught how to find, interpret and act on the information she oversees on engravings.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s the final step of the process that really makes a difference when every second counts &ndash; if our products are is easy to find and the person&rsquo;s information is readily available, then that&rsquo;s going to help a lot,&rdquo; says Dr LePage.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know exactly how many lives we&rsquo;ve saved, but if it&rsquo;s even a handful, then that&rsquo;s something to be proud of, because without this quality control process we have at MedicAlert then perhaps some people would fall through the cracks and healthcare professionals wouldn&rsquo;t be able to respond as quickly, or in the right way, in an emergency.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Dr LePage is responsible for reviewing all MedicAlert engravings for new members who join and their have not had their application authenticated by a GP. This is a quality control measure to help ensure the safety and protection of all MedicAlert members.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>For more information about this service or to check that your engraving is up to date call <a href=&quot;1800 88 22 22&quot;>1800 88 22 22</a>.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Better than the rest',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-08-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:14:46','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(250,685,2,0,17,'NEW PRODUCTS: We&rsquo;ve never looked so good!',NULL,NULL,'new-products-weandrsquove-never-looked-so-good',0,NULL,'<p>A MedicAlert medical ID is something you should be wearing everyday, so why not make sure it looks great too. You may even like to grab a couple of different styles &ndash; one for work and daytime use and one to help you look great and feel protected at that special occasion.</p>\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s our latest offering:</p>\r\n<p><strong>The gold look has never been so affordable!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Introducing our new coloured curb stainless steel bracelets. These stunning bracelets not only look beautiful, but will last beautifully too. Paired with the genuine MedicAlert&reg; medical ID, you can stay protected in style.</p>\r\n<p>Available in a yellow gold or rose gold curb chain bracelets, these stainless steel products are a perfect addition to any outfit. In fact they&rsquo;ve been so popular that our rose gold style is currently sold out, but you can still order it as we have new stock arriving in September this year. To be the first to get your hands on these incredibly popular new styles make sure you <a href=&quot;/rose-gold-coloured-stainless-steel-curb-chain-bracelet&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>order yours today.</a></p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/yellowgoldrosegold.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;yellowgoldrosegold.jpg (23 KB)&quot; width=&quot;686&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Never out of style</strong></p>\r\n<p>Our new leather wrap around bracelets are smart, affordable and will never go out of fashion. Available in four colours &ndash; black, brown, rusty red and tan &ndash; they provide the perfect stylish, laid-back look.</p>\r\n<p>Made from durable leather and complete with the genuine MedicAlert&reg; medical ID, you can stay protected in style no matter where you go. <a href=&quot;/braided-triple-leather-band&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Order yours today.</a></p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/leatherwrap.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;leatherwrap.jpg (18 KB)&quot; width=&quot;686&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; /> </p>\r\n<p><strong>A bit of bling!</strong></p>\r\n<p>Great for casual or formal wear, our new gemstone bracelets are as gorgeous as they are practical. Available in howlite, rose quartz and amethyst, these beautiful products have a convenient stretchy design and no clasp.</p>\r\n<p>Paired with the genuine MedicAlert&reg; emblem, you can stay protected in true style. <a href=&quot;/stainless-steel-howlite-gemstone-stretch-bracelet-&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Order your new gemstone bracelet today.</a></p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/productthree_copy1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;productthree_copy1.jpg (8 KB)&quot; width=&quot;686&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; /></p>\r\n<p><strong>The real deal</strong></p>\r\n<p>Introducing our new 9ct gold range. Be the first to purchase our new range of stunning 9 carat gold medical IDs. With a variety of designs to choose from, including new emblem styles and bracelet chains, there&rsquo;s a product to suit every style.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> <img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/news-and-resources/newsletter/goldrange2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;goldrange2.jpg (25 KB)&quot; width=&quot;686&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; /></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Browse through our new gold range to<a href=&quot;/products&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;> find a medical ID that&rsquo;s right for you.</a></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'NEW PRODUCTS: We&rsquo;ve never looked so good!',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,'/uploads/news-and-resources/images/medic-alert-logo.jpg',NULL,NULL,'2016-08-01','2020-12-31',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:16:01','2018-01-31 07:13:08',NULL),(251,687,1,0,0,'Personal Alarms &amp; Monitoring',NULL,NULL,'personal-alarms-and-monitoring',0,'<p>At MedicAlert we&#039;re always looking for ways to ensure that our members benefit. We are often contacted by members who are looking for specific in-home protection with alarm and monitoring services apart from the protection they receive from being a MedicAlert member.</p>\r\n<p>We can advise that we offer this additional security and service through our new partnership with Tunstall Healthcare.</p>\r\n<h2> </h2>','<h2>Who is Tunstall?</h2>\r\n<p>Tunstall Healthcare is a world leading provider of assistive technology solutions. Operating in over 50 countries and supporting more than 3.6 million people. Their connected care solutions play a key role in helping older people and those with long-term health needs to live safely and independently in their own homes.</p>\r\n<p>Tunstall offers a range of innovative products including landline, mobile and wearable personal alarms, fall detectors, activity monitors and environmental sensors. Tunstall&#039;s solutions enable freedom and independence by unobtrusively monitoring risks to your safety within the home.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<h2>How does the Tunstall monitoring service work?</h2>\r\n<p>The central hub of a Tunstall monitoring service is the personal medical alarm that can be used to quickly and easily make contact with their 24 hour monitoring centres.</p>\r\n<p>To raise an alarm call, the user can simply press the help button on either their pendant or the base alarm unit. The alarm then dials the 24 hour monitoring centres and a Tunstall Operator will answer over the alarm.</p>\r\n<p>The user does not need to be next to their phone or alarm unit. The Operators will be able to hear the user and other happenings in the home; and they will ask how they can best help. They will coordinate the most appropriate response such as contacting a family member or friend, after-hours doctor or emergency services. The Tunstall Operator will always stay on the line with the user until help arrives.</p>','<h2>Why is the Tunstall - MedicAlert partnership and service right for you?</h2>\r\n<p>Partnering with MedicAlert will ensure MedicAlert members receive a wider range of services and support that will assist members to remain independent and safe, even in an emergency.</p>\r\n<p>Tunstall is a leading provider for alarm and monitoring services in the home environment. With over 55 years of global experience Tunstall are proud to be an innovation and technology leader, providing trusted personal alarm solutions, and are a long established provider to government, retirement villages and community care organisations.</p>\r\n<p>Tunstall pride themselves on their people, value person-centred care and put clients at the heart of their operations. Their caring staff continually go above and beyond to assist on a daily basis, ensuring they are renowned for their exceptional customer service standards.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p><img class=&quot;img-responsive&quot; style=&quot;display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot; src=&quot;/uploads/partners/mafwebtunstalltopwidebannerwhite.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;mafwebtunstalltopwidebannerwhite.jpg (39 KB)&quot; width=&quot;601&quot; height=&quot;137&quot; /></p>','<h2>Enquire now<br /><br /></h2>\r\n<p><strong>To enquire about this service, please call Tunstall on 1800 611 528.</strong> To receive this MedicAlert member only discount simply quote your MedicAlert number at the time of your enquiry. If you&#039;re not a current MedicAlert member it&#039;s easy to <a title=&quot;How to join link&quot; href=&quot;/how-to-become-a-member&quot;>join online</a>. <strong>This special offer is not applicable for existing customers of Tunstall or its partners.</strong></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>MedicAlert will be paid a commission from Tunstall for members that sign up to receive the Tunstall alarm and monitoring service. See MedicAlert&rsquo;s <a href=&quot;/terms-and-conditions&quot;>Terms and Conditions </a>for full details.<br /><br /></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Personal Alarms &amp; Monitoring | MedicAlert',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 19:45:41','2016-10-26 06:46:53',NULL),(252,688,1,0,0,'Bracelet sizing and engraving tips','Bracelet Sizing Guide',NULL,'bracelet-sizing-and-engraving-tips',0,'<p>It&rsquo;s important to make sure your MedicAlert bracelet fits properly, so that it is both secure and comfortable. The total length of the product you select includes the medical ID, chain (band) and clasp.</p>\r\n<p>Following is a guide to help you determine which size bracelet is best for you.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Please note:</strong> it is your responsibility to make sure your wrist measurement is correct when placing your order. A small fee may be incurred for any alterations or adjustments made after your order has been completed. Some styles are not able to be adjusted.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Measuring instructions</strong></h3>\r\n<p><iframe src=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/embed/ISJ7hW1POAU?rel=0&amp;showinfo=0&quot; width=&quot;640&quot; height=&quot;360&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen=&quot;allowfullscreen&quot;></iframe></p>\r\n<p>Use a measuring tape or a piece of string and a <a href=&quot;/uploads/documents/ruler.pdf&quot;>ruler</a> to measure your wrist around the widest point. Ensure the measurement is firm, but not tight.</p>\r\n<p>Left and right wrist sizes may vary, so be sure to measure the wrist you intend to wear your bracelet on.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have your wrist measurement, you will need to add some allowance to get the right fit (see &lsquo;length to add&rsquo; column in the below table). This will provide enough room to secure the clasp and turn over the medical ID without removing the bracelet.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<table style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot; border=&quot;1&quot;>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p><strong>Bracelet style</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p><strong>Length to add</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Cable-Link</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>3cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Curb chain</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>1.5cm*</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Bangle</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>1.5cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Belcher</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>2.5cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Byzantine chain bracelet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>2cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Expanda band</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>1cm*</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Gemstones</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>0cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Gold infinity chain bracelet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>2cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Gold napoli chain bracelet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>2cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Large ball charm bracelet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>4cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Leather</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>1.5cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Silicone</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>1cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Swarovski charm/pearl bracelet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>3cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=&quot;217&quot;>\r\n<p>Swarovski crystal</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=&quot;209&quot;>\r\n<p>2cm</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>*For young children, please reduce the length to add by 0.5cm for each style.</p>','<h2 id=&quot;engrave-section&quot;>General engraving guidelines</h2>\r\n<p>Words are not to be hyphenated and one space is required between each word. Standard medical terminology and medically recognised abbreviations may be used.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;><strong>Common medical abbreviations</strong></p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>A/F Atrial fibrillation/Atrial flutter</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>AVR Aortic valve replacement</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>CABG Coronary artery bypass graft</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>CAD Coronary artery disease</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>COAD Chronic obstructive airways disease</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>COPD Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>CVA Cerebrovascular accident</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>ERYC Erythromycin</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>GORD Gastro-oesophageal reflux disorder</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>IBS Irritable bowel syndrome</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>IHD Ischaemic heart disease</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>MVR Mitral valve replacement</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>NSAIDS Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>TIA Transient ischaemic attack</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;>TX Transplant</p>\r\n<p style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;> </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong><br /> Common examples of what should be included on the medical ID:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>Allergies causing anaphylaxis &ndash; Penicillin, bee stings, nuts. Shown on medical ID as &ldquo;ALLERGY: PENICILLIN ANAPHYLAXIS&rdquo;.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>Medical conditions - Diabetes, Epilepsy, Asthma, CABG, MVR, Autism, Dementia. These are written on your medical ID as &ldquo;EPILEPSY&rdquo; or &ldquo;DIABETES, CABG&rdquo;. Consider including next-of-kin contact number on the medical ID for people with Autism or Dementia.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>Implanted Medical Devices - Pacemaker. Shown on medical ID as &ldquo;PACEMAKER&rdquo;.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>Long term medications that are not likely to change &ndash; Warfarin, Insulin, Steroids. Shown on medical ID as &ldquo;ON: WARFARIN&rdquo;.</li>\r\n<li style=&quot;text-align: left;&quot;>Other options that can be included &ndash; Organ donor, blood group and no known allergies. Shown on medical ID as &ldquo;ORGAN DONOR&rdquo;, &ldquo;B/G: 0-&rdquo;, &ldquo;NO KNOWN ALLERGIES&rdquo;.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Note: Any information not engraved on your medical ID will be recorded on your personal file that can be accessed by emergency services and healthcare professionals by calling the 24/7 hotline number on your medical ID, and listed on your Membership/Emergency Assist Card.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Australia Medic Alert Foundation</strong></p>\r\n<p>GPO Box 9963, In Your Capital City</p>\r\n<p>FREECALL 1800 88 22 22 | FREEFAX 1800 643 259</p>\r\n<p><a href=&quot;mailto:enquiries@medicalert.org.au &quot;>enquiries@medicalert.org.au </a></p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Bracelet sizing and engraving tips | MedicAlert',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 20:02:37','2017-06-16 01:23:24',NULL),(253,690,1,0,0,'Quick checkout',NULL,NULL,'quick-checkout',0,'<p>Simply enter your credit card information below to make a payment.</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,99,'Quick Checkout | MedicAlert',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,'2016-10-13 22:25:44','2016-10-26 06:41:12',NULL),(254,670,6,0,0,'Bupa',NULL,NULL,'bupa',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,999,'Bupa',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,'2016-10-13 18:05:05','2016-10-31 05:16:40','2016-10-31 15:46:40'),(255,10,1,0,0,'Terms and Conditions',NULL,NULL,'terms-and-conditions',1,'<div>\r\n<h3>TERMS AND CONDITIONS OF MEMBERSHIP</h3>\r\n<p><em>1. Introduction<br /></em></p>\r\n<p>1.1 By applying to become a Member you agree to be bound by these Conditions as varied from time to time.  Please read them carefully.</p>\r\n<p>1.2 We reserve the right to amend these Conditions at any time.</p>\r\n<p><em>2. Benefits of Membership<br /></em></p>\r\n<p>2.1 Upon becoming a Member, we will provide the following benefits to you:</p>\r\n<p>2.1.1 provision of a Medic Alert Identification Number;</p>\r\n<p>2.1.2 creation and maintenance of an electronic record of all your Health Information;</p>\r\n<p>2.1.3 secure web based access to your Health Information using any user name or password provided to you or generated in connection with your Membership;</p>\r\n<p>2.1.4 the right to purchase from us Personalised Medic Alert Products for your own personal use;</p>\r\n<p>2.1.5 through the 24/7 Medic Alert Emergency Response Service, disclosure of your Health Information to any professional emergency responders and Health Practitioners requesting such information in circumstances where they have quoted your Medic Alert Identification Number or other personal information which identifies you; and</p>\r\n<p>2.1.6 access to our newsletter and other Member publications.</p>\r\n<p>2.2 The above benefits will only be made available to you for so long as your Membership Fees are fully paid up.</p>\r\n<p><em>3. Applying for Membership<br /></em></p>\r\n<p>3.1 You may only apply for Membership:</p>\r\n<p>3.1.1 on your own behalf; or</p>\r\n<p>3.1.2 on behalf of any minor or adult person who is not capable of applying for Membership for him or herself and for whom you are acting as a Responsible Person.</p>\r\n<p>3.2 An application for Membership may be for annual or Membership for any other period we may permit.</p>\r\n<p>3.3 You may only apply for Membership by providing to us a completed Membership Application Form online through the Website or by post or other means of delivery acceptable to us.</p>\r\n<p>3.4 An application for Membership must be accompanied by payment of the relevant Membership Fee Application Fee (if any).</p>\r\n<p><em>4. Membership Fees<br /></em></p>\r\n<p>4.1 Membership Fees are inclusive of GST.</p>\r\n<p>4.2 Continuation of your annual and other periodic Membership is subject to payment of your annual or other periodic Membership Fee;</p>\r\n<p>4.3 You must pay your Membership Fees by the due date for payment.</p>\r\n<p>4.4 We will take reasonable steps to notify you of your Membership Fee falling due before the due date for payment.</p>\r\n<p><em>5. Your Information<br /></em></p>\r\n<p>5.1 We may collect your 